00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:12.640
[Amit Varma]: Mr. Tharoor, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:13.920
[Amit Varma]: Yes, hi, how are you?

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:15.640
[Guest]: I mean, good to good to be with you.

00:03:15.640 --> 00:03:16.640
[Guest]: Thanks so much.

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:20.840
[Guest]: And I requested this interview really to talk about your wonderful book, The Paradoxical

00:03:20.840 --> 00:03:22.520
[Guest]: Prime Minister, which I enjoyed reading a lot.

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:25.200
[Guest]: But as it happens, we are recording on January 2nd.

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:28.640
[Guest]: And yesterday, Mr. Modi gave a rather paradoxical interview as well.

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:29.960
[Guest]: What did you think of that?

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:34.520
[Amit Varma]: Well, I have to confess that I was actually doing something else myself and didn't watch

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:35.520
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:39.640
[Amit Varma]: But I read the excerpts in the newspapers and I've now got hold of the transcript, which

00:03:39.640 --> 00:03:40.840
[Amit Varma]: I haven't fully read.

00:03:40.840 --> 00:03:49.520
[Amit Varma]: I'm a bit taken aback by both his very defensive tone and his the fact that he actually didn't

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:56.560
[Amit Varma]: offer any new compelling reasons why we should, as Indian voters, want to reward him for his

00:03:56.560 --> 00:03:58.080
[Amit Varma]: five years in office.

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:02.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, all the Achyutini promise haven't come for anybody.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:08.520
[Amit Varma]: He is defensive about demonetization, which was a disaster for large numbers of our population.

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:13.160
[Amit Varma]: And some of the vainglorious boasts about the love of crores of people for him make

00:04:13.160 --> 00:04:17.480
[Amit Varma]: me wonder whether he's living in his own bubble and doesn't see the damage he's done in this

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:18.480
[Amit Varma]: country.

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:21.360
[Amit Varma]: And that's perceived by the voters of this country.

00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:26.680
[Guest]: One of the things that struck me about your book was the title of the book, where you

00:04:26.680 --> 00:04:31.200
[Guest]: called it the paradoxical prime minister and not the hypocritical prime minister, which

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:35.400
[Guest]: seems to indicate that you sort of gave him the benefit of the doubt to start with.

00:04:35.400 --> 00:04:39.000
[Guest]: And you yourself were befuddled by kind of what went wrong.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.200
[Guest]: So can you tell me a little bit about your journey of how you looked at Narendra Modi

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:44.200
[Amit Varma]: over time?

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:48.300
[Amit Varma]: Well, you know, as I've described in the book, I mean, I obviously when I was in the States

00:04:48.300 --> 00:04:55.000
[Amit Varma]: when 2002 happened, and I shared everybody's anger and shame and revulsion at the horrors

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:00.520
[Amit Varma]: that were perpetrated in Gujarat in 2002, and therefore the fact that Narendra Modi

00:05:00.520 --> 00:05:07.200
[Amit Varma]: had presided over all of this and in many accounts was seen as culpable for having encouraged

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:12.440
[Amit Varma]: some of the worst elements, all of that made me look at him as scant.

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:19.600
[Amit Varma]: I therefore didn't ever make any effort to meet him and met him entirely by accident,

00:05:19.600 --> 00:05:26.720
[Amit Varma]: sort of backstage at a lunch at the Prabhasi Bharatiya Divas in Chennai in January of 2009,

00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:30.880
[Amit Varma]: and was very pleasantly surprised because he was impressive, he was engaging, and what

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:37.600
[Amit Varma]: he had to say was not stuff that I could have expected from the, shall we say, the accounts

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:40.640
[Amit Varma]: of him that had demonized him.

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:44.200
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if you want me to recount one of the tales, but I mean, I remember saying

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:50.240
[Amit Varma]: to him, for example, you know, why did you allow all this to happen?

00:05:50.240 --> 00:05:51.480
[Amit Varma]: And he said, I did everything I could.

00:05:51.480 --> 00:05:54.080
[Amit Varma]: I called in the army.

00:05:54.080 --> 00:05:57.080
[Amit Varma]: When there was no joy in that, I then went on to, you know, what the situation is today

00:05:57.080 --> 00:05:58.880
[Amit Varma]: for Muslims in Gujarat.

00:05:58.880 --> 00:06:03.600
[Amit Varma]: I said, I believe a sort of ghetto has been created, a sort of mini Pakistan, as people

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:06.320
[Amit Varma]: call it, and is that healthy for the future of Gujarat?

00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:08.640
[Amit Varma]: And he said, they prefer it that way.

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:11.400
[Amit Varma]: So that conversation wasn't going anywhere else, and then I said, well, look, you know,

00:06:11.400 --> 00:06:16.040
[Amit Varma]: one of the concerns is that you're not doing anything for Muslims in Gujarat in the aftermath

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:17.040
[Amit Varma]: of all of this.

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:18.800
[Amit Varma]: And he said, let me tell you a story.

00:06:18.800 --> 00:06:25.120
[Amit Varma]: And he said, you know, this is exactly the charge that was laid on me by a commission

00:06:25.120 --> 00:06:26.440
[Amit Varma]: that had come from Delhi.

00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:29.840
[Amit Varma]: I assume this was the Sachar commission, but he didn't use the term.

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:34.920
[Amit Varma]: And he said, these people came and they came to my office and they said, we hear you've

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:37.120
[Amit Varma]: done nothing for Muslims in Gujarat.

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:38.640
[Amit Varma]: So he said, sit down and write.

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:42.400
[Amit Varma]: And he said, they all took out their notebooks and their pens very dutifully.

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:49.200
[Amit Varma]: And I looked at them and I said, you write, I'm saying this, I have done nothing for Muslims

00:06:49.200 --> 00:06:50.200
[Amit Varma]: in Gujarat.

00:06:50.200 --> 00:06:54.160
[Amit Varma]: And he says, they took out their pens and their notebooks and they started writing furiously

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:56.540
[Amit Varma]: that I've done nothing for Muslims in Gujarat.

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:57.540
[Amit Varma]: And he's a very good storyteller.

00:06:57.540 --> 00:06:58.540
[Amit Varma]: So he paused dramatically.

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:01.720
[Amit Varma]: And then he said, write this also.

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:05.020
[Amit Varma]: I have done nothing for Hindus in Gujarat.

00:07:05.020 --> 00:07:09.600
[Amit Varma]: And then as they also looked up with surprise, he said, I have only worked for Gujaratis.

00:07:09.600 --> 00:07:12.320
[Amit Varma]: Now, I must say, that was a very effective story.

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:16.000
[Amit Varma]: It's the kind of message you expect from a secular political leader.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:17.760
[Amit Varma]: And I thought that was a that was a.

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:22.920
[Amit Varma]: So I went to a feeling there was something here about this guy that perhaps the earlier

00:07:22.920 --> 00:07:26.960
[Amit Varma]: accounts of his conduct in 2002 and so on had not captured.

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:31.760
[Amit Varma]: And then I saw another side of him, which I couldn't and my lawyers won't allow me to

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:35.040
[Amit Varma]: be explicit about what it was he said.

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:40.160
[Amit Varma]: But when I was minister of state for external affairs a few months after this episode, less

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:45.960
[Amit Varma]: than a year after this episode, the UAE authorities in the country I was visiting asked me to

00:07:45.960 --> 00:07:53.360
[Amit Varma]: intervene on an unusual problem they were having, which was that their company, Dubai

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:58.520
[Amit Varma]: Ports World, had bought up the British company P&O, which is managing a number of Indian

00:07:58.520 --> 00:07:59.520
[Amit Varma]: ports.

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:03.040
[Amit Varma]: So all the contracts had to be rewritten to change P&O to Dubai Ports World.

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:07.360
[Amit Varma]: It was basically the same people, the same staff and managers, but it was merely a legal

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:08.360
[Amit Varma]: exercise.

00:08:08.360 --> 00:08:12.440
[Amit Varma]: And whereas in every state it had worked very smoothly, in Gujarat they were having a problem.

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:13.640
[Amit Varma]: And could I do something about it?

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:18.560
[Amit Varma]: So I, taking advantage of this earlier encounter with him in January, I called Narendra Modi,

00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:19.560
[Amit Varma]: chief minister of Gujarat.

00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:21.880
[Amit Varma]: He was very prompt in taking the call.

00:08:21.880 --> 00:08:23.200
[Amit Varma]: And I said, look, this is what I'm doing.

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:25.800
[Amit Varma]: I'm in the UAE on official visit.

00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:27.360
[Amit Varma]: And there seems to be this problem, you know.

00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:29.960
[Amit Varma]: It's a very routine matter.

00:08:29.960 --> 00:08:30.960
[Amit Varma]: What's the issue here?

00:08:30.960 --> 00:08:33.440
[Amit Varma]: Why can't we just sign this and get it done with?

00:08:33.440 --> 00:08:37.840
[Amit Varma]: And he said something which, as I said, I'm not allowed legally to quote, but which made

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:39.680
[Amit Varma]: it very clear that he was not going to do so.

00:08:39.680 --> 00:08:44.880
[Amit Varma]: And he explained, he said, if you want the UAE to invest in my states, by all means,

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:49.360
[Amit Varma]: tell them to come to the interior and I will give them land and electricity and good roads

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:52.960
[Amit Varma]: and drinking water and all the connections they want.

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:56.640
[Amit Varma]: But I will not be giving them a port because I don't want to have Islamic terrorists running

00:08:56.640 --> 00:08:57.640
[Amit Varma]: around my state.

00:08:57.640 --> 00:09:05.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, this kind of thinking, this kind of talk was, to my mind, somewhat more revelatory

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:11.520
[Amit Varma]: of the Narendra Modi who I'd heard less sort of flattering things about.

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:17.560
[Amit Varma]: And then, of course, we had the Narendra Modi of the election campaign a few years later,

00:09:17.560 --> 00:09:23.080
[Amit Varma]: the man who became the prime ministerial candidate of the BJP, having really built up a reputation

00:09:23.080 --> 00:09:29.960
[Amit Varma]: for somewhat incendiary campaigning in Gujarat that was hostile to minorities, that was hostile

00:09:29.960 --> 00:09:34.640
[Amit Varma]: to that was very overtly Hindutva oriented.

00:09:34.640 --> 00:09:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And then he starts, particularly in the immediate aftermath of his victory, saying the most

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:45.160
[Amit Varma]: amazingly liberal things, the sabka saad, sabka vikas, for instance, or the assurance

00:09:45.160 --> 00:09:51.000
[Amit Varma]: that I will be a prime minister for all Indians, or saying that the Constitution is my only

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:56.840
[Amit Varma]: holy book and the parliament is the temple of democracy, moving away from that aggressively

00:09:56.840 --> 00:10:00.080
[Amit Varma]: Hindutva identity he had earlier cultivated.

00:10:00.080 --> 00:10:03.720
[Amit Varma]: And so, yes, I was prepared to give him the benefit of the doubt at that time, because

00:10:03.720 --> 00:10:09.720
[Amit Varma]: my view was that, first of all, one has to respect the electorate, which has put him

00:10:09.720 --> 00:10:12.040
[Amit Varma]: there and they've just put him there.

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:16.400
[Amit Varma]: We can't act as if we have contempt for their electoral votes.

00:10:16.400 --> 00:10:23.120
[Amit Varma]: But equally, by applauding the sentiments that he's expressing, we are now laying very

00:10:23.120 --> 00:10:27.320
[Amit Varma]: clearly the yardstick by which his future action should be judged.

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:31.760
[Amit Varma]: We are applauding these things that you have said, these liberal pronouncements, and we

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:38.480
[Amit Varma]: will judge you by your ability to fulfill and live up to these yardsticks, these liberal

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:39.800
[Amit Varma]: pronouncements.

00:10:39.800 --> 00:10:42.960
[Amit Varma]: That was the spirit in which I welcomed his initial remarks.

00:10:42.960 --> 00:10:47.080
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, it wasn't very well understood in my own party, and I was pilloried and so

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:48.520
[Amit Varma]: on by many.

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:52.040
[Amit Varma]: But within six months of his assent, I had recanted.

00:10:52.040 --> 00:10:59.440
[Amit Varma]: I published a book called India Shastra, Reflections on the Nation in Our Time, in December 2014.

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:03.640
[Amit Varma]: I think the copyright page for publishers reads as January 2015.

00:11:03.640 --> 00:11:08.600
[Amit Varma]: But in that I wrote, in the introduction to what was a collection of essays that had been

00:11:08.600 --> 00:11:15.520
[Amit Varma]: published over the preceding six or seven years, in the introduction I wrote that Mr.

00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:21.560
[Amit Varma]: Modi really represents a contradiction because he says all these very liberal things, but

00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:28.720
[Amit Varma]: he rests for political support and viability on the most illiberal elements in Indian society,

00:11:28.720 --> 00:11:33.800
[Amit Varma]: the RSS types, the Hindutva types, the anti-science, the rewriting history elements, all of these

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:37.560
[Amit Varma]: because they love jihadis and the ghar wapasi types, all of whom had emerged from the woodwork

00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:39.560
[Amit Varma]: in those first few months.

00:11:39.560 --> 00:11:45.560
[Amit Varma]: And I said that in this contradiction may lie the seeds of his future failure.

00:11:45.560 --> 00:11:47.720
[Amit Varma]: And this was published in December 2014.

00:11:47.720 --> 00:11:53.040
[Amit Varma]: So when I wrote the paradoxical Prime Minister, I was able to begin with the words, I told

00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:54.320
[Amit Varma]: you so.

00:11:54.320 --> 00:12:00.400
[Amit Varma]: And to that degree, my own journey, as you put it, Amit, had in a sense been vindicated,

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:04.400
[Amit Varma]: almost as if Mr. Modi spent four years proving me right.

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:05.800
[Guest]: Which is very gracious of him.

00:12:05.800 --> 00:12:10.320
[Guest]: And in your book, you do a beautiful job of documenting, you know, the various paradoxical

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:11.320
[Guest]: aspects of Modi.

00:12:11.320 --> 00:12:13.400
[Guest]: You know, I noted down nine of them while reading the book.

00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:17.760
[Guest]: But before I ask you about them, I want to ask you some broader questions about broader

00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:22.200
[Guest]: paradoxes to do with politics and India.

00:12:22.200 --> 00:12:28.680
[Guest]: And the first of those is that it has always seemed to me that the imperatives of politics

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:35.680
[Guest]: make it impossible for anyone who enters politics to actually hold on to whatever principles

00:12:35.680 --> 00:12:36.680
[Guest]: they might have.

00:12:36.680 --> 00:12:40.240
[Guest]: Because once you enter politics, you have to make compromises, you have to cater to

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:44.600
[Guest]: your interest groups who fund you, you have to cater to different vote banks.

00:12:44.600 --> 00:12:49.640
[Guest]: And you have to, you know, cynically pursue the end over the means.

00:12:49.640 --> 00:12:52.160
[Guest]: And it can even be morally corrosive.

00:12:52.160 --> 00:12:57.400
[Guest]: Now, as someone who himself has had a very distinguished career in public life at the

00:12:57.400 --> 00:13:02.480
[Guest]: UN and as a novelist and a writer, and who joined politics rather late, is that something

00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:04.200
[Guest]: you'd have any views on?

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:07.640
[Guest]: Is it really what are the tugs on the pulse like?

00:13:07.640 --> 00:13:13.760
[Amit Varma]: So what you said is right, that to a great extent, any democratically elected politician

00:13:13.760 --> 00:13:19.280
[Amit Varma]: has to be responsive to voters, to backers, to funders, all of these sources, everything

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:21.120
[Amit Varma]: you said is true.

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:25.840
[Amit Varma]: But that doesn't mean you sell your soul, because if you did, then what are you contributing

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:30.000
[Amit Varma]: to the nation's political values and the political discourse?

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:35.760
[Amit Varma]: It seems to me that something I realized even at the UN was that you had to have ideals.

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:39.640
[Amit Varma]: If you didn't have ideals, you shouldn't be at the UN because you may as well go off and

00:13:39.640 --> 00:13:44.240
[Amit Varma]: be a banker or a lawyer or an accountant or whatever else, where you can mortgage your

00:13:44.240 --> 00:13:48.600
[Amit Varma]: ideals to the service of your client and merely judge your success by the bottom line in your

00:13:48.600 --> 00:13:49.600
[Amit Varma]: bank account.

00:13:49.600 --> 00:13:56.200
[Amit Varma]: But if you are in an organization like the UN, and the same logic applies to politics,

00:13:56.200 --> 00:14:00.560
[Amit Varma]: you must have ideals, you must have principles, you must have things you seek to pursue, but

00:14:00.560 --> 00:14:06.360
[Amit Varma]: you must have the maturity and the wisdom to realize you can only pursue them within

00:14:06.360 --> 00:14:09.640
[Amit Varma]: the limitations of what is politically possible.

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:15.840
[Amit Varma]: So the UN, I had to be responsive to 192 member states and the Security Council, the 15 very

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:17.240
[Amit Varma]: powerful countries.

00:14:17.240 --> 00:14:20.760
[Amit Varma]: I can't sit around acting as if I own the world.

00:14:20.760 --> 00:14:21.760
[Amit Varma]: I don't.

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:27.920
[Amit Varma]: I am an employee of the United Nations organization, which is in turn controlled by 192 governments.

00:14:27.920 --> 00:14:33.760
[Amit Varma]: And there is an interplay of interests, beliefs, concerns, policy preferences of these governments

00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:36.880
[Amit Varma]: in which I will have to make the right judgment as to what compromises to make.

00:14:36.880 --> 00:14:41.920
[Amit Varma]: And the judgments I make are essentially where my values and principles are tested.

00:14:41.920 --> 00:14:46.920
[Amit Varma]: Now you apply that logic to Indian politics, what happens is this.

00:14:46.920 --> 00:14:51.960
[Amit Varma]: There are some things, for example, that I find I cannot say because they're at variance

00:14:51.960 --> 00:14:54.560
[Amit Varma]: with the policies adopted by my party.

00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:58.720
[Amit Varma]: Now if I were completely cynical, I'd swallow my own beliefs and mouth the party line.

00:14:58.720 --> 00:15:05.080
[Amit Varma]: If I say, look, I understand that it's important for the party to take the stand it's taking.

00:15:05.080 --> 00:15:06.920
[Amit Varma]: I'm not going to say what I don't believe.

00:15:06.920 --> 00:15:12.640
[Amit Varma]: I could have a very different approach in which where I speak, I speak of my own conviction,

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:16.720
[Amit Varma]: and where I can't agree with my party, I just choose to stay silent.

00:15:16.720 --> 00:15:21.600
[Amit Varma]: That's one way of limiting the extent to which you're compromising your convictions.

00:15:21.600 --> 00:15:26.200
[Amit Varma]: Another example would come from when you're talking about responding to voters.

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:27.520
[Amit Varma]: You listen to your voters.

00:15:27.520 --> 00:15:29.360
[Amit Varma]: That is extremely important.

00:15:29.360 --> 00:15:35.440
[Amit Varma]: And when you find that your voters feel strongly enough about something, you have all the more

00:15:35.440 --> 00:15:38.600
[Amit Varma]: an obligation to listen to them because you are their representative.

00:15:38.600 --> 00:15:44.280
[Amit Varma]: If at the end of the day they personalize you, that their beliefs matter, then you do

00:15:44.280 --> 00:15:46.880
[Amit Varma]: choose to compromise in your position.

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:53.640
[Amit Varma]: Whereas if you find that they are wrongheaded, you can argue to them and try and educate

00:15:53.640 --> 00:15:55.760
[Amit Varma]: them to see things in your point of view.

00:15:55.760 --> 00:15:57.840
[Amit Varma]: So I found myself both happening.

00:15:57.840 --> 00:16:05.400
[Amit Varma]: That is on Section 377, for example, the vast majority of my voters disagreed with me.

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:11.320
[Amit Varma]: And I had to, in various occasions, to people from the church, to people of my voters, explain

00:16:11.320 --> 00:16:13.880
[Amit Varma]: my position on 377.

00:16:13.880 --> 00:16:16.560
[Amit Varma]: And of course, I took care to stress this is not about sex.

00:16:16.560 --> 00:16:17.760
[Amit Varma]: It's about freedom.

00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:21.840
[Amit Varma]: It's about the rights of Indian citizens like you and me to be themselves.

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:26.960
[Amit Varma]: And that argument I did not compromise on, even though had there been a poll taken, the

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:32.280
[Amit Varma]: vast majority of my voters would have been against my stand on Section 377.

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:33.640
[Amit Varma]: But they came around in the end.

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:38.140
[Amit Varma]: And once the court, the Supreme Court, took the decision it did, I actually looked good

00:16:38.140 --> 00:16:41.480
[Amit Varma]: in retrospect in many of their eyes.

00:16:41.480 --> 00:16:47.120
[Amit Varma]: Then you take something like Sabarimana, where the vast majority of my constituents disagreed

00:16:47.120 --> 00:16:49.160
[Amit Varma]: with my initial position.

00:16:49.160 --> 00:16:55.800
[Amit Varma]: And I came around to the realization that I had been wrong in framing the issue merely

00:16:55.800 --> 00:17:02.360
[Amit Varma]: in terms of my familiar categories of principles of equality and constitutionalism.

00:17:02.360 --> 00:17:07.160
[Amit Varma]: And that when you're touching matters of religious faith, you are actually talking about something

00:17:07.160 --> 00:17:12.120
[Amit Varma]: that goes very deep into the heart of people's beliefs and worship.

00:17:12.120 --> 00:17:19.880
[Amit Varma]: And so I came around to becoming an explainer of their concerns rather than somebody who

00:17:19.880 --> 00:17:24.600
[Amit Varma]: would have stuck to what all my normal liberal constituency expected of me.

00:17:24.600 --> 00:17:29.040
[Amit Varma]: And as a result, of course, I have been denounced by the very people who on most other issues

00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:31.160
[Amit Varma]: I would have seen as my friends.

00:17:31.160 --> 00:17:36.020
[Amit Varma]: Would I have come to that conclusion if I had not been an elected political representative

00:17:36.020 --> 00:17:41.520
[Amit Varma]: in Kerala, meeting people every day who were expressing the passion of their views?

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:42.520
[Amit Varma]: Very clearly, no.

00:17:42.520 --> 00:17:47.360
[Amit Varma]: If I had just been a liberal columnist or writer sitting either in New York or in New

00:17:47.360 --> 00:17:50.600
[Amit Varma]: Delhi, I probably would never have changed my mind on Sabarimana.

00:17:50.600 --> 00:17:56.220
[Amit Varma]: So their politics did bring about a change, and it's part of the compromise that democratic

00:17:56.220 --> 00:17:58.200
[Amit Varma]: representation involves.

00:17:58.200 --> 00:18:00.720
[Amit Varma]: But I don't see myself as having mortgaged my principles.

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:06.500
[Amit Varma]: If their arguments had not convinced me of their own merit, I would not have changed.

00:18:06.500 --> 00:18:12.780
[Amit Varma]: But the realization that when you frame the issue as one of sanctity, that you're touching

00:18:12.780 --> 00:18:18.100
[Amit Varma]: on profound matters of faith and of religious practice, that just south of Trivandrum is

00:18:18.100 --> 00:18:23.040
[Amit Varma]: in Kanyakumari, the famous Kumari Amman temple from which Kanyakumari gets its name to the

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:27.720
[Amit Varma]: virgin form of the goddess, where men are not allowed in the inner sanctum.

00:18:27.720 --> 00:18:31.700
[Amit Varma]: And if for thousands of years men have not been allowed there, if you've applied the

00:18:31.700 --> 00:18:35.580
[Amit Varma]: Supreme Court's gender equality principle, men will be able to go there.

00:18:35.580 --> 00:18:40.280
[Amit Varma]: And the day a man steps into that sanctum sanctorum, the sanctity of that temple for

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:43.100
[Amit Varma]: millions of women worshippers is completely destroyed.

00:18:43.100 --> 00:18:47.380
[Amit Varma]: And you have to ask yourself as a political representative what is right, the principle

00:18:47.380 --> 00:18:53.120
[Amit Varma]: of gender equality or the meaning of this temple as a sanctified place to its believers

00:18:53.120 --> 00:18:54.440
[Amit Varma]: and worshippers?

00:18:54.440 --> 00:18:57.800
[Amit Varma]: It becomes a very different debate when you think of it that way.

00:18:57.800 --> 00:18:59.560
[Guest]: Yeah, matter of colliding principles.

00:18:59.560 --> 00:19:00.560
[Guest]: I completely get that.

00:19:00.560 --> 00:19:05.980
[Guest]: And my sort of, I mean, I don't want to derail this by, you know, focusing on Sabarimala.

00:19:05.980 --> 00:19:10.840
[Guest]: So just moving on from there, my slightly related question there is that, is it then

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:17.140
[Guest]: entirely fair to judge politicians by how much they implement the promises they might

00:19:17.140 --> 00:19:20.300
[Guest]: have made when the promises could have been fairly high minded?

00:19:20.300 --> 00:19:25.480
[Guest]: But if you consider the incentives, once they get to power, they include in general, two

00:19:25.480 --> 00:19:29.280
[Guest]: particular kinds of incentives, that is incentives of the interest groups, which put them in

00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:32.480
[Guest]: power and which will want them to implement favorable policies.

00:19:32.480 --> 00:19:38.240
[Guest]: And number two, the incentives which come from whichever vote banks they might be cultivating,

00:19:38.240 --> 00:19:42.280
[Guest]: and their actions might run inimicable to the general interest.

00:19:42.280 --> 00:19:46.360
[Guest]: Because, you know, in one case, they'd be working on behalf of interest groups.

00:19:46.360 --> 00:19:50.280
[Guest]: On the other hand, they might have to cater to a certain kind of identity politics that

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:53.040
[Guest]: has dominated our discourse through the decades.

00:19:53.040 --> 00:19:57.720
[Guest]: And in the case of Modi, you could argue that there's even a sort of a third force, which

00:19:57.720 --> 00:20:02.520
[Guest]: is the RSS, which he's always been part of, which is exerting its own kind of nativist

00:20:02.520 --> 00:20:04.160
[Guest]: pressures.

00:20:04.160 --> 00:20:09.320
[Guest]: And is it even realistic to then assume that all of this high minded liberal talk, as you

00:20:09.320 --> 00:20:15.480
[Guest]: put it, the commitment to pluralism, and so on, can actually, you know, play out in action?

00:20:15.480 --> 00:20:18.600
[Guest]: And would anyone in his place be able to do something?

00:20:18.600 --> 00:20:24.560
[Amit Varma]: OK, so as a general principle, I would say that most of the promises politicians make

00:20:24.560 --> 00:20:27.960
[Amit Varma]: do not conflict with the interests of the majority of voters, or they wouldn't make

00:20:27.960 --> 00:20:28.960
[Amit Varma]: them.

00:20:28.960 --> 00:20:33.920
[Amit Varma]: So by and large, when a politician says something high minded or otherwise, it's because he

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:35.780
[Amit Varma]: knows his voters want to hear it.

00:20:35.780 --> 00:20:39.560
[Amit Varma]: And if he therefore is unable to fulfill it, he needs to explain to his voters why he hasn't.

00:20:39.560 --> 00:20:42.880
[Amit Varma]: I've stuck to that policy in my two terms in office.

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:46.160
[Amit Varma]: I explain everything that I promised to do and how I've tried to do it.

00:20:46.160 --> 00:20:50.280
[Amit Varma]: And if I've failed, I explain why I failed and leave it to the voters to judge whether

00:20:50.280 --> 00:20:52.160
[Amit Varma]: I should be blamed or not for that failure.

00:20:52.160 --> 00:20:56.120
[Amit Varma]: And that's, I think, an important part of political accountability.

00:20:56.120 --> 00:20:58.720
[Amit Varma]: But in the case of Mr. Modi, it was a more cynical exercise.

00:20:58.720 --> 00:21:03.300
[Amit Varma]: He actually knew that the core Hindu vote was his anyway.

00:21:03.300 --> 00:21:05.240
[Amit Varma]: That vote wasn't going to go away.

00:21:05.240 --> 00:21:10.720
[Amit Varma]: And so the so-called high minded statements you're referring to were made to attract the

00:21:10.720 --> 00:21:17.440
[Amit Varma]: undecided voters who were not Hindutva oriented, who were possibly even directly negative about

00:21:17.440 --> 00:21:23.760
[Amit Varma]: Hindutva, but who were attracted by the other aspects of his message, particularly the developmental

00:21:23.760 --> 00:21:25.000
[Amit Varma]: message.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:30.880
[Amit Varma]: And the cynicism of that is, let me take you to a different political environment to give

00:21:30.880 --> 00:21:31.920
[Amit Varma]: you a parallel.

00:21:31.920 --> 00:21:40.320
[Amit Varma]: In America, it is often critiqued that the Republican Party runs on a campaign involving

00:21:40.320 --> 00:21:47.480
[Amit Varma]: guns, God and gays, the sort of cultural nationalism of the American right, and thereby attracts

00:21:47.480 --> 00:21:52.080
[Amit Varma]: the votes of a lot of working class people, small town people, salaried people and so

00:21:52.080 --> 00:21:53.080
[Amit Varma]: on.

00:21:53.080 --> 00:21:59.040
[Amit Varma]: And having come to power on that, it then unmasks its real agenda, which is to put more

00:21:59.040 --> 00:22:01.520
[Amit Varma]: money in the pockets of the plutocrats.

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:08.400
[Amit Varma]: And it essentially devotes its political energy to financial and fiscal policies that benefit

00:22:08.400 --> 00:22:13.120
[Amit Varma]: the tiny mass of their supporters and backers and funders.

00:22:13.120 --> 00:22:16.880
[Amit Varma]: That is, in other words, cultural nationalism becoming the bait.

00:22:16.880 --> 00:22:17.880
[Amit Varma]: And then you switch.

00:22:17.880 --> 00:22:19.640
[Amit Varma]: It's called bait and switch.

00:22:19.640 --> 00:22:22.600
[Amit Varma]: You switch to your real agenda, which is economics.

00:22:22.600 --> 00:22:26.920
[Amit Varma]: I would suggest that what we've seen with Mr. Modi is also bait and switch.

00:22:26.920 --> 00:22:32.840
[Amit Varma]: But it's the exact reverse of the Republican approach, which is that economics has been

00:22:32.840 --> 00:22:33.840
[Amit Varma]: the bait.

00:22:33.840 --> 00:22:34.840
[Amit Varma]: He's talked about Vikas.

00:22:34.840 --> 00:22:36.640
[Amit Varma]: He's talked about Gujarat Inc.

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:40.080
[Amit Varma]: He's talked about how much he's been able to do and how much he's going to do for India.

00:22:40.080 --> 00:22:41.080
[Amit Varma]: And people have voted for him.

00:22:41.080 --> 00:22:47.200
[Amit Varma]: And then having come to power, instead of focusing on results in that area, he has merely

00:22:47.200 --> 00:22:53.080
[Amit Varma]: unleashed some of the most retrogressive forces of cultural nationalism across the country.

00:22:53.080 --> 00:22:56.960
[Amit Varma]: And the only conclusion one can inescapably draw is that that must have been his real

00:22:56.960 --> 00:23:03.120
[Amit Varma]: agenda, that the economics was all talk and the real action is in cow vigilantism, is

00:23:03.120 --> 00:23:11.320
[Amit Varma]: in car, Roper sees and love Jihad is in communal polarization, is in the murder even of Muslims

00:23:11.320 --> 00:23:17.720
[Amit Varma]: for being too Muslim is in the compulsory ization of Bharat Mata, etc., etc., etc.

00:23:17.720 --> 00:23:22.840
[Amit Varma]: All of that cultural nationalism has been dominant articulation and priority of this

00:23:22.840 --> 00:23:28.080
[Amit Varma]: government having won votes on the basis of something quite different.

00:23:28.080 --> 00:23:29.080
[Guest]: I couldn't agree with you more.

00:23:29.080 --> 00:23:33.240
[Guest]: I think, you know, many of the people who might have been taken in by his promises of

00:23:33.240 --> 00:23:36.640
[Guest]: development should now listen to his words and say that, you know, you fooled me once,

00:23:36.640 --> 00:23:39.080
[Guest]: shame on you, fool me twice, shame on me.

00:23:39.080 --> 00:23:44.320
[Guest]: But my question was really more about a broader sort of question about politics in general.

00:23:44.320 --> 00:23:50.800
[Guest]: The next paradox I want to ask you about is a paradox of the idea of India.

00:23:50.800 --> 00:23:55.920
[Guest]: You know, Mr. Tagore's phrase and something that, you know, you bring up in your book,

00:23:55.920 --> 00:24:00.640
[Guest]: and you know, the objection that you know, at length, you quote the Indian upadhyay talking

00:24:00.640 --> 00:24:03.280
[Guest]: about the constitution and railing against it.

00:24:03.280 --> 00:24:07.520
[Guest]: And I think there is a question there that must be addressed by liberal elites such as

00:24:07.520 --> 00:24:08.520
[Guest]: you and me.

00:24:08.520 --> 00:24:14.040
[Guest]: And it was in fact, liberal elites who framed the constitution and you could make a criticism

00:24:14.040 --> 00:24:17.960
[Guest]: that look, the constitution didn't actually reflect the soul of the people.

00:24:17.960 --> 00:24:21.960
[Guest]: It was these westernized liberal elites in a sense, Nehru and Gang were really British

00:24:21.960 --> 00:24:25.600
[Guest]: liberals in a sense, in you know, where their thinking came from.

00:24:25.600 --> 00:24:27.120
[Guest]: And I mean that in a good way.

00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:35.040
[Guest]: But one, there is that paradox that forcing a liberal way of life on an illiberal country,

00:24:35.040 --> 00:24:39.560
[Guest]: isn't that act itself illiberal, you know, and that's one paradox.

00:24:39.560 --> 00:24:44.640
[Guest]: And the other paradox that then is that if now and I'm not saying this is necessarily

00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:50.740
[Guest]: the case, but if now the country is to assert its illiberalism and want the constitution

00:24:50.740 --> 00:24:54.520
[Guest]: to reflect that, on what grounds are we to stand in the way?

00:24:54.520 --> 00:24:56.680
[Amit Varma]: Well, that's a very interesting question.

00:24:56.680 --> 00:25:02.760
[Amit Varma]: I have to say that it's something which one doesn't have easy answers for, because I actually

00:25:02.760 --> 00:25:08.740
[Amit Varma]: accept the critique that the constitution, as the Indian panther put it, is full of imported

00:25:08.740 --> 00:25:14.240
[Amit Varma]: Western ideas written by Anglophile lawyers in English, which is not from his point of

00:25:14.240 --> 00:25:16.640
[Amit Varma]: view, an authentic Indian language.

00:25:16.640 --> 00:25:21.880
[Amit Varma]: And in these circumstances, you're really looking at a question that says, I'm prepared

00:25:21.880 --> 00:25:29.120
[Amit Varma]: to say, so what if these ideas are good, if these ideas are actually ideas that in many,

00:25:29.120 --> 00:25:34.280
[Amit Varma]: many ways would improve the lives of Indians, why shouldn't we adopt them even if they've

00:25:34.280 --> 00:25:35.740
[Amit Varma]: come from abroad?

00:25:35.740 --> 00:25:38.120
[Amit Varma]: Is any culture truly pristine?

00:25:38.120 --> 00:25:42.520
[Amit Varma]: Hasn't India been open to external influences since time immemorial?

00:25:42.520 --> 00:25:46.800
[Amit Varma]: Didn't we welcome these outsiders when they came, whether it was the Jews fleeing the

00:25:46.800 --> 00:25:51.520
[Amit Varma]: destruction of their temple by the Babylonians and then by the Romans, whether it was Islam

00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:57.200
[Amit Varma]: coming to the south of India as a message, as it were, during the lifetime of the prophet,

00:25:57.200 --> 00:26:02.120
[Amit Varma]: whether it was Zoroastrianism, the Parsis coming as refugees fleeing Muslim persecution

00:26:02.120 --> 00:26:04.160
[Amit Varma]: in Persia in the seventh century.

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:11.960
[Amit Varma]: All of these examples suggest to me that you actually have a society which has had a lot

00:26:11.960 --> 00:26:17.680
[Amit Varma]: of openness to various influences and which, as Swami Vivekananda argued, has always found

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:23.680
[Amit Varma]: the secret of its survival in the acceptance of difference, the acceptance that other people

00:26:23.680 --> 00:26:24.960
[Amit Varma]: of other ways were doing things.

00:26:24.960 --> 00:26:30.560
[Amit Varma]: So it may be, in your view, a somewhat illiberal society, and if you look at caste relations

00:26:30.560 --> 00:26:37.680
[Amit Varma]: and so on, it certainly does seem illiberal, but it has also been a society which, by the

00:26:37.680 --> 00:26:43.120
[Amit Varma]: practice of acceptance, and I stress the word acceptance rather than merely tolerance, has

00:26:43.120 --> 00:26:51.840
[Amit Varma]: actually allowed multiple forms of worship to exist and flourish on Indian soil.

00:26:51.840 --> 00:26:57.360
[Amit Varma]: And the strength of that is what I think makes India ripe for a liberal constitution.

00:26:57.360 --> 00:27:00.840
[Amit Varma]: It is not a liberal imposition on illiberal country.

00:27:00.840 --> 00:27:08.320
[Amit Varma]: It is a liberal overlay on a system which, because of its respect for difference and

00:27:08.320 --> 00:27:13.840
[Amit Varma]: its acceptance for difference, permits, if you like, modern constitutional principles

00:27:13.840 --> 00:27:19.000
[Amit Varma]: to be addressed in this older society.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:22.680
[Amit Varma]: One of the interesting distinctions that this causes is the following.

00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:29.000
[Amit Varma]: In Western democracies, the individual citizen is the only one who has rights.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:34.000
[Amit Varma]: In India, we have the individual rights that have come to us through Western democracy,

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:36.560
[Amit Varma]: but we also have community and group rights.

00:27:36.560 --> 00:27:40.560
[Amit Varma]: We recognize things like personal laws of different religious communities, for which

00:27:40.560 --> 00:27:44.560
[Amit Varma]: there is no equivalent in the United States or in most Western democracies.

00:27:44.560 --> 00:27:46.120
[Amit Varma]: Now, what does this mean?

00:27:46.120 --> 00:27:51.000
[Amit Varma]: This means that you have got an overlay, but that overlay is not incompatible with the

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:57.480
[Amit Varma]: idea of rights that already pre-existed in that society, in our society.

00:27:57.480 --> 00:28:01.840
[Amit Varma]: So I don't consider it illiberal, and I'll take you back to the beginning of your initial

00:28:01.840 --> 00:28:02.840
[Amit Varma]: comment.

00:28:02.840 --> 00:28:07.880
[Amit Varma]: I would argue that the liberalism that you say might have been an imposition on this

00:28:07.880 --> 00:28:14.200
[Amit Varma]: society is actually what has made a lot of the evolution of this society possible.

00:28:14.200 --> 00:28:22.920
[Amit Varma]: That without the constitution of 1950, a Mayawati, a Dalit woman, who for 3,000 years, it would

00:28:22.920 --> 00:28:28.640
[Amit Varma]: have been unthinkable to see a Dalit woman ruling the land of Arya Vrata, this Dalit

00:28:28.640 --> 00:28:33.680
[Amit Varma]: woman has been elected three times as chief minister of UP, thanks to that liberal constitution.

00:28:33.680 --> 00:28:39.280
[Amit Varma]: A man of very humble origins who sold tea on a railway station platform has become prime

00:28:39.280 --> 00:28:44.400
[Amit Varma]: minister of India because of the liberal constitution and the institutions that were created and

00:28:44.400 --> 00:28:45.920
[Amit Varma]: nurtured under it.

00:28:45.920 --> 00:28:51.160
[Amit Varma]: So I would argue that in fact, our society needs this constitution, needs these liberal

00:28:51.160 --> 00:28:56.720
[Amit Varma]: values and is what it is because these values have shaped us for 71 years.

00:28:56.720 --> 00:29:01.560
[Guest]: I take your point, though I'm a little sceptical about how individual rights and group rights

00:29:01.560 --> 00:29:06.460
[Guest]: can coexist, because it seems to me that there is a dissonance there, which eventually leads

00:29:06.460 --> 00:29:07.460
[Guest]: to conflict.

00:29:07.460 --> 00:29:08.840
[Amit Varma]: But my other question there is that...

00:29:08.840 --> 00:29:13.720
[Amit Varma]: Let me answer that before you move on from it, which is, to my mind, I've actually written

00:29:13.720 --> 00:29:18.760
[Amit Varma]: an article in the Northern Journal of International Law about 30 years ago, making this point

00:29:18.760 --> 00:29:24.400
[Amit Varma]: that they coexist only in a context in which the individual has the right to opt out.

00:29:24.400 --> 00:29:29.520
[Amit Varma]: In other words, culture means that, yes, you can have Muslim personal law, but it can't

00:29:29.520 --> 00:29:30.520
[Amit Varma]: be coercion.

00:29:30.520 --> 00:29:32.040
[Amit Varma]: Culture should not be coercion.

00:29:32.040 --> 00:29:38.040
[Amit Varma]: If a Muslim woman chooses to marry a non-Muslim or marry a Muslim under civil law, she has

00:29:38.040 --> 00:29:40.840
[Amit Varma]: the right to do so under our constitution.

00:29:40.840 --> 00:29:46.840
[Amit Varma]: And that's essentially the argument that says, for those who wish to abide by it, group rights

00:29:46.840 --> 00:29:47.840
[Amit Varma]: exist.

00:29:47.840 --> 00:29:51.880
[Amit Varma]: For those who wish to opt out, the constitution protects their individual rights.

00:29:51.880 --> 00:29:54.920
[Amit Varma]: And to my mind, that gives you the way in which the two can coexist.

00:29:54.920 --> 00:29:56.320
[Guest]: Fair enough.

00:29:56.320 --> 00:30:01.240
[Guest]: And, you know, if we accept that, let's say that to begin with, we have a liberal, relatively

00:30:01.240 --> 00:30:05.280
[Guest]: liberal constitution, I still feel it's illiberal in many ways, in that it doesn't protect free

00:30:05.280 --> 00:30:08.920
[Guest]: speech enough, and the right to property is not a fundamental right, and so on.

00:30:08.920 --> 00:30:13.020
[Guest]: But leaving that aside, if we accept that the constitution is more liberal than society

00:30:13.020 --> 00:30:19.240
[Guest]: is even today, then, you know, the question that brings me to is a question, you know,

00:30:19.240 --> 00:30:24.560
[Guest]: how a society becomes liberal, is it a top down process, as you're saying it can be that

00:30:24.560 --> 00:30:26.840
[Guest]: a constitution can play a part in that?

00:30:26.840 --> 00:30:29.560
[Guest]: Or should it necessarily be a bottom up process?

00:30:29.560 --> 00:30:33.840
[Guest]: Like, for example, you're in the political marketplace, you're part of the supply end

00:30:33.840 --> 00:30:37.920
[Guest]: of the political marketplace, and there is a demand and you're catering to, and it's

00:30:37.920 --> 00:30:42.480
[Guest]: always seemed to me that you have to change the demand and first at the battle is first

00:30:42.480 --> 00:30:45.640
[Guest]: a cultural battle, and then a political battle.

00:30:45.640 --> 00:30:50.200
[Guest]: And if you don't change the demand end, and if the demand end is largely illiberal, then

00:30:50.200 --> 00:30:54.920
[Guest]: you're never going to get really liberal policies from the supply end, because politicians will

00:30:54.920 --> 00:30:55.920
[Guest]: reflect society.

00:30:55.920 --> 00:30:58.400
[Amit Varma]: Yes, and no, I mean, you're broadly right.

00:30:58.400 --> 00:31:02.640
[Amit Varma]: And I can't claim that the preponderance of evidence would be against your argument, your

00:31:02.640 --> 00:31:04.720
[Amit Varma]: argument is actually right.

00:31:04.720 --> 00:31:09.840
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I have noticed, particularly in the context of 377, that the judiciary has far

00:31:09.840 --> 00:31:15.360
[Amit Varma]: more courage than politicians, because politicians don't think beyond the prejudices of their

00:31:15.360 --> 00:31:20.920
[Amit Varma]: government, whereas the judiciary has no such fetters and is free to advocate certain principles

00:31:20.920 --> 00:31:23.000
[Amit Varma]: and values that it holds dear.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:29.160
[Amit Varma]: But you know, again, my counter argument involves precisely that, that the liberal constitution

00:31:29.160 --> 00:31:33.160
[Amit Varma]: we have created has also created these different institutions.

00:31:33.160 --> 00:31:38.480
[Amit Varma]: It's not as if the only change in our society is a change that can be voted for by a majority

00:31:38.480 --> 00:31:40.240
[Amit Varma]: of members of Parliament.

00:31:40.240 --> 00:31:43.320
[Amit Varma]: There are changes that are coming through the judicial route.

00:31:43.320 --> 00:31:47.960
[Amit Varma]: Many would argue that there's a flurry of Supreme Court judgments over the last 15,

00:31:47.960 --> 00:31:52.840
[Amit Varma]: 20 years have expanded the notion of women's rights in India way beyond anything that our

00:31:52.840 --> 00:31:57.040
[Amit Varma]: society has known in the past, or that perhaps a government would have dared to introduce

00:31:57.040 --> 00:31:59.000
[Amit Varma]: or a Parliament would have voted for.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:05.320
[Amit Varma]: So let's accept that in a democracy, there are many institutions of democracy.

00:32:05.320 --> 00:32:10.280
[Amit Varma]: The judiciary is one of them, and it sometimes thinks beyond what Parliament is capable of

00:32:10.280 --> 00:32:11.280
[Amit Varma]: doing.

00:32:11.280 --> 00:32:17.240
[Amit Varma]: But the media to which you belong is also an extremely important institution of democracy,

00:32:17.240 --> 00:32:24.480
[Amit Varma]: and it can help promote change by what it depicts of cultural practices and social values.

00:32:24.480 --> 00:32:30.400
[Amit Varma]: Certainly, the India in which I grew up and which I left at the age of 19 to go to graduate

00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:34.960
[Amit Varma]: school in the West, and the India to which I returned at the age of 51, were very different

00:32:34.960 --> 00:32:41.320
[Amit Varma]: Indias when it comes to things like, for example, sexual mores, when it comes to conspicuous

00:32:41.320 --> 00:32:46.360
[Amit Varma]: consumption, when it comes to the overt public display of affluence, all sorts of things.

00:32:46.360 --> 00:32:52.800
[Amit Varma]: A cultural change had occurred, and I think it was a change that was enabled by mass media,

00:32:52.800 --> 00:32:58.080
[Amit Varma]: by media showing examples of all of these, by media showing that this was what was practiced

00:32:58.080 --> 00:33:02.920
[Amit Varma]: elsewhere in the world, by media showing that the world was moving on and India should perhaps

00:33:02.920 --> 00:33:06.800
[Amit Varma]: catch up, or some sections of India found it attractive to catch up with the rest of

00:33:06.800 --> 00:33:07.800
[Amit Varma]: the world.

00:33:07.800 --> 00:33:11.880
[Amit Varma]: So change comes in all sorts of ways, not just through politicians.

00:33:11.880 --> 00:33:17.160
[Amit Varma]: Politicians in some cases can only reflect what their voters are prepared to tolerate.

00:33:17.160 --> 00:33:21.600
[Amit Varma]: In some cases, they will have the courage of their convictions to take things forward.

00:33:21.600 --> 00:33:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And in some cases, the politicians are operating in domains in which the public themselves

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:30.880
[Amit Varma]: don't know really any better or any worse.

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:32.320
[Amit Varma]: And so there is an educated role.

00:33:32.320 --> 00:33:38.360
[Amit Varma]: When Manmohan Singh stood up in Parliament in 1991 and said, as finance minister paraphrasing

00:33:38.360 --> 00:33:44.080
[Amit Varma]: Victor Hugo, that no power on earth can stop an idea whose time has come, what was he saying?

00:33:44.080 --> 00:33:49.400
[Amit Varma]: He was basically saying at that point that the economic underpinnings of your normal

00:33:49.400 --> 00:33:53.400
[Amit Varma]: life in India that you've always known are suddenly going to change.

00:33:53.400 --> 00:33:57.840
[Amit Varma]: Now, you can't say that a lot of voters would have asked for it, but they didn't know they

00:33:57.840 --> 00:34:00.080
[Amit Varma]: could ask for it, as it were.

00:34:00.080 --> 00:34:05.720
[Amit Varma]: Most voters in India were living within the protected and somewhat overregulated economy

00:34:05.720 --> 00:34:07.320
[Amit Varma]: that we had up to then.

00:34:07.320 --> 00:34:11.360
[Amit Varma]: But suddenly when everything became possible, when foreign goods could come in, when restrictions

00:34:11.360 --> 00:34:15.920
[Amit Varma]: were lifted, when companies could expand, etc., etc., etc., the same people, the same

00:34:15.920 --> 00:34:18.000
[Amit Varma]: voters embraced these things.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:21.640
[Amit Varma]: So it's only when it comes to matters that people are sensitive about, which are usually

00:34:21.640 --> 00:34:26.520
[Amit Varma]: social, religious, cultural matters, that politicians are a bit more constrained.

00:34:26.520 --> 00:34:31.720
[Amit Varma]: When it comes to things like economic policy, when it comes to things like most of the foreign

00:34:31.720 --> 00:34:36.920
[Amit Varma]: policy issues in our country and so on, the voters do give politicians the freedom to

00:34:36.920 --> 00:34:38.960
[Amit Varma]: pursue their convictions and their beliefs.

00:34:38.960 --> 00:34:39.960
[Guest]: Fair enough.

00:34:39.960 --> 00:34:45.180
[Guest]: Before I move on to talking about your book per se, just one final general question.

00:34:45.180 --> 00:34:49.740
[Guest]: As your anecdote at the start about Modi indicated, where he said that I do nothing for the Muslims

00:34:49.740 --> 00:34:54.320
[Guest]: of Gujarat, I do nothing for the Hindus of Gujarat, I focus on the Gujaratis, which is

00:34:54.320 --> 00:34:56.260
[Guest]: a remarkable rhetorical turn.

00:34:56.260 --> 00:34:58.000
[Guest]: And he is a master of rhetoric.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:03.340
[Guest]: And it's often been said about him that he focuses purely on optics, that he's great

00:35:03.340 --> 00:35:06.840
[Guest]: at campaigning and not so much governing.

00:35:06.840 --> 00:35:10.400
[Guest]: And one always assumed that this is going to come back and bite him at some point, maybe

00:35:10.400 --> 00:35:11.660
[Guest]: 2019.

00:35:11.660 --> 00:35:15.800
[Guest]: But my counterpoint to that is that maybe he sees something we don't, which is that

00:35:15.800 --> 00:35:21.160
[Guest]: maybe only the optics matters in the sense that what has happened over the last few years,

00:35:21.160 --> 00:35:27.360
[Guest]: exacerbated to some extent by social media, but not entirely, is that, you know, the journalist

00:35:27.360 --> 00:35:31.160
[Guest]: Walter Lippmann in the early 1900s wrote a book called Public Opinion, where the first

00:35:31.160 --> 00:35:35.180
[Guest]: chapter was titled, The World Out There and The World Inside Our Heads, where he pointed

00:35:35.180 --> 00:35:40.320
[Guest]: out that people construct a world inside their heads, and then whether or not it corresponds

00:35:40.320 --> 00:35:43.040
[Guest]: to the real world outside, they stick to that world.

00:35:43.040 --> 00:35:47.960
[Guest]: And it seems to me that social media makes it possible to meet like minded people, even

00:35:47.960 --> 00:35:53.520
[Guest]: if they're fellow bigots or mythogenists or whatever, who might validate those worst impulses,

00:35:53.520 --> 00:35:55.940
[Guest]: and you know, strengthen your belief in them.

00:35:55.940 --> 00:36:01.320
[Guest]: And it's very easy to form echo chambers, and then be imprisoned in those narratives,

00:36:01.320 --> 00:36:03.120
[Guest]: which cannot be touched by reality.

00:36:03.120 --> 00:36:07.400
[Guest]: So once you believe that narrative, for example, if you believe in narrative that Hindu civilization

00:36:07.400 --> 00:36:12.040
[Guest]: is under threat, and everything was glorious once and blah, blah, blah, then what is happening

00:36:12.040 --> 00:36:17.040
[Guest]: outside doesn't really matter so much like after demonetization, which I thought was

00:36:17.040 --> 00:36:20.760
[Guest]: a disaster and the biggest assault on property rights in human history, I was sure they would

00:36:20.760 --> 00:36:21.960
[Guest]: lose in UP.

00:36:21.960 --> 00:36:23.520
[Guest]: But they won by a landslide.

00:36:23.520 --> 00:36:27.120
[Guest]: And it seemed to me that what had actually happened, the suffering that people had gone

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:31.480
[Guest]: through didn't affect the way they voted because it already made up a narrative inside the

00:36:31.480 --> 00:36:32.520
[Guest]: heads.

00:36:32.520 --> 00:36:36.800
[Guest]: And if that is the case, maybe Mr. Modi is smarter than we think, because he knows then

00:36:36.800 --> 00:36:40.800
[Guest]: on that only the narrative matters and the reality of things doesn't matter.

00:36:40.800 --> 00:36:41.800
[Guest]: So to hell with governance.

00:36:41.800 --> 00:36:44.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that's a very depressing thought.

00:36:44.640 --> 00:36:48.600
[Amit Varma]: Because I think the narrative worked for Mr. Modi in UP because it was very soon after

00:36:48.600 --> 00:36:52.920
[Amit Varma]: the elections, very soon after the demonetization of the elections took place.

00:36:52.920 --> 00:36:58.040
[Amit Varma]: And there was still time for a very, very clever narrative to seize the imaginations

00:36:58.040 --> 00:36:59.040
[Amit Varma]: of people.

00:36:59.040 --> 00:37:02.320
[Amit Varma]: One of which, by the way, was oddly enough, the politics of class resentment.

00:37:02.320 --> 00:37:04.920
[Amit Varma]: It was basically saying, yeah, you've suffered.

00:37:04.920 --> 00:37:06.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, the rich have suffered much more.

00:37:06.920 --> 00:37:09.160
[Amit Varma]: The rich are the guys who've really got hit because of this.

00:37:09.160 --> 00:37:10.660
[Amit Varma]: So we did this for you.

00:37:10.660 --> 00:37:12.400
[Amit Varma]: And the poor said, wow, yeah, you're right.

00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:13.960
[Amit Varma]: You know, those rich guys have suffered.

00:37:13.960 --> 00:37:15.840
[Amit Varma]: Let's reward Modi.

00:37:15.840 --> 00:37:19.960
[Amit Varma]: But with time, that argument, that narrative doesn't hold, because the poor are able to

00:37:19.960 --> 00:37:22.280
[Amit Varma]: see that they're the ones who lost jobs.

00:37:22.280 --> 00:37:23.760
[Amit Varma]: They're the ones who lost their savings.

00:37:23.760 --> 00:37:25.400
[Amit Varma]: They're the ones who suffered.

00:37:25.400 --> 00:37:29.760
[Amit Varma]: Whereas the rich are back to being rich again and are carrying on oblivious.

00:37:29.760 --> 00:37:34.760
[Amit Varma]: And they realize that that old narrative that Modi had sold them in the UP election doesn't

00:37:34.760 --> 00:37:35.760
[Amit Varma]: work.

00:37:35.760 --> 00:37:39.800
[Amit Varma]: And on top of that, that they've elected a deeply unsatisfactory government, which has

00:37:39.800 --> 00:37:46.680
[Amit Varma]: let them down really in all sorts of ways, and which has created an environment in which

00:37:46.680 --> 00:37:53.080
[Amit Varma]: the BJP's unpopularity is now being widely talked about in the regime of Yogi Adityanath.

00:37:53.080 --> 00:37:58.760
[Amit Varma]: And for these reasons, I think that you may be right about the whole management of narrative

00:37:58.760 --> 00:38:01.000
[Amit Varma]: as an answer in the short term.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:04.840
[Amit Varma]: I don't believe it works indefinitely in the long term.

00:38:04.840 --> 00:38:11.600
[Amit Varma]: And I do think that we're going to find in the elections of 2019, Modi is going to find

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:14.760
[Amit Varma]: it very difficult to spin the same yarn twice.

00:38:14.760 --> 00:38:21.880
[Amit Varma]: How does a young man in Kanpur, who voted for Mr. Modi in 2014 because Modi painted

00:38:21.880 --> 00:38:26.240
[Amit Varma]: this brilliant portrait of jobs sort of tumbling out of the woodwork for him because he's going

00:38:26.240 --> 00:38:29.740
[Amit Varma]: to attract all this investment and create so much business, and he's going to get rid

00:38:29.740 --> 00:38:33.520
[Amit Varma]: of all the sclerotic practices of the old regime, and jobs are going to be there, and

00:38:33.520 --> 00:38:37.800
[Amit Varma]: this young man will have a job and five years later, the same guy doesn't have a job, none

00:38:37.800 --> 00:38:41.320
[Amit Varma]: of the fantasies that were depicted for him have come true.

00:38:41.320 --> 00:38:42.560
[Amit Varma]: Why would he vote for Modi again?

00:38:42.560 --> 00:38:47.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, how do you how long can a narrative be a substitute for the reality experienced

00:38:47.880 --> 00:38:49.440
[Guest]: by the human person?

