00:39:56.120 --> 00:40:01.800
[Guest]: Mr. Tharoor, you outline a number of ways in which Modi is paradoxical in your book.

00:40:01.800 --> 00:40:06.000
[Guest]: And the first one which strikes me as very interesting and which I think gave some hope

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:13.680
[Guest]: to a lot of liberal people who voted for Modi in 2014 was you spoke about how in Gujarat,

00:40:13.680 --> 00:40:15.680
[Guest]: like it's actually a triple paradox.

00:40:15.680 --> 00:40:17.600
[Guest]: He began as an RSS person.

00:40:17.600 --> 00:40:22.160
[Guest]: But when he was chief minister of Gujarat, he actually marginalized a lot of the extreme

00:40:22.160 --> 00:40:24.240
[Guest]: Hindu elements like the VHP and so on.

00:40:24.240 --> 00:40:25.280
[Guest]: He fought with Togadia.

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:29.600
[Guest]: He kicked out Gurdan Duffadia from his cabinet, though he's, you know, back in his good books

00:40:29.600 --> 00:40:30.600
[Guest]: again.

00:40:30.600 --> 00:40:35.000
[Guest]: And a lot of people assume that he might do the same when he is in power at the center

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:40.160
[Guest]: and that we won't go in this very Hindutva Bharat Mata ki Jai direction.

00:40:40.160 --> 00:40:44.560
[Guest]: And instead, he will live up to his promises on development and be Vikash Purush instead

00:40:44.560 --> 00:40:46.600
[Guest]: of Hindu Riddhe Samrat.

00:40:46.600 --> 00:40:49.400
[Guest]: This I mean, did this take you by surprise?

00:40:49.400 --> 00:40:55.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I actually did think, as you said, that that's what he he he might do, because first

00:40:55.960 --> 00:41:02.560
[Amit Varma]: of all, Vikash Purush is was what he tried to depict himself as for the bulk of his time

00:41:02.560 --> 00:41:06.420
[Amit Varma]: in Gujarat, and therefore that became his calling card for the nation.

00:41:06.420 --> 00:41:13.080
[Amit Varma]: But second, I thought that it's also a better thing to run for reelection on, because, you

00:41:13.080 --> 00:41:17.280
[Amit Varma]: know, the temporary satisfaction you get from beating people of other religions on the head

00:41:17.280 --> 00:41:22.520
[Amit Varma]: is unlikely to be a sustainable asset, whereas improving people's livelihoods and making

00:41:22.520 --> 00:41:25.720
[Amit Varma]: them feel good about themselves will obviously be new votes against.

00:41:25.720 --> 00:41:30.040
[Amit Varma]: I was very much thinking that he would focus on that.

00:41:30.040 --> 00:41:34.720
[Amit Varma]: But as I realized, as I said, within six months of his coming to power, it couldn't work for

00:41:34.720 --> 00:41:39.320
[Amit Varma]: him that way, because his support base, the very people who needed to go out and knock

00:41:39.320 --> 00:41:44.220
[Amit Varma]: on those doors and win those campaigns for him, actually happened to be people for whom

00:41:44.220 --> 00:41:50.220
[Amit Varma]: the only thing that mattered was the Hindu Hridaya Samrat's work.

00:41:50.220 --> 00:41:56.160
[Amit Varma]: And it is very, very sad in some ways that our own political and constitutional system

00:41:56.160 --> 00:42:01.360
[Amit Varma]: kind of reinforced that, because we have elections somewhere or the other every six months, thanks

00:42:01.360 --> 00:42:03.440
[Amit Varma]: to the vagaries of the parliamentary system.

00:42:03.440 --> 00:42:05.800
[Amit Varma]: Some stay to the others going to the polls.

00:42:05.800 --> 00:42:11.440
[Amit Varma]: And Modi, in his desire to consolidate power, became the nation's campaigner in chief, the

00:42:11.440 --> 00:42:16.160
[Amit Varma]: Pradhan Pracharak, quite literally in the sense of campaigning, rather than the Pradhan

00:42:16.160 --> 00:42:17.960
[Amit Varma]: Sevak that he claimed to be.

00:42:17.960 --> 00:42:21.640
[Amit Varma]: He was not doing Desh Ka Seva, he was doing Bhaja Pa Ka Prachar.

00:42:21.640 --> 00:42:26.880
[Amit Varma]: And in that process, what you saw throughout the country was a Modi who had to pander to

00:42:26.880 --> 00:42:31.860
[Amit Varma]: the instincts of his followers, his campaigners, the guys who are going out knocking on doors

00:42:31.860 --> 00:42:36.200
[Amit Varma]: and sticking up posters and banners, were the Hindutva elements, the RSS elements, the

00:42:36.200 --> 00:42:38.000
[Amit Varma]: VHP and the Bajrang Dal.

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:41.960
[Amit Varma]: These were the characters who were there to support Mr. Modi so he could win state election

00:42:41.960 --> 00:42:43.680
[Amit Varma]: after state election.

00:42:43.680 --> 00:42:47.280
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, his message became tailored entirely to them.

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:52.840
[Amit Varma]: And he was also handicapped in his ability to say something when they got out of hand

00:42:52.840 --> 00:42:57.400
[Amit Varma]: and actually murdered people or flogged them on YouTube or stabbed them to death in a very

00:42:57.400 --> 00:42:59.440
[Amit Varma]: disgracefully public manner.

00:42:59.440 --> 00:43:04.040
[Amit Varma]: Then instead of disavowing them, as one would expect any decent prime minister to do in

00:43:04.040 --> 00:43:09.680
[Amit Varma]: terms of exercising the moral leadership of the nation, Mr. Modi went mysteriously silent.

00:43:09.680 --> 00:43:13.320
[Amit Varma]: But the reason was he couldn't afford to antagonize the very people without whose efforts he couldn't

00:43:13.320 --> 00:43:14.860
[Amit Varma]: win all these states.

00:43:14.860 --> 00:43:17.680
[Amit Varma]: So the whole thing became circular, you see, in this way.

00:43:17.680 --> 00:43:21.360
[Guest]: And just as an aside, it's probably unfair to ask you this because you may not know him

00:43:21.360 --> 00:43:28.280
[Guest]: well enough, but do you think he has any core beliefs of his own or is he sort of the quintessential

00:43:28.280 --> 00:43:33.640
[Guest]: sociopath who'll do whatever it takes to further his immediate self-interest?

00:43:33.640 --> 00:43:38.040
[Amit Varma]: That's a difficult question for me to answer because it's easy enough for an opposition

00:43:38.040 --> 00:43:40.680
[Amit Varma]: MP to say the latter.

00:43:40.680 --> 00:43:45.720
[Amit Varma]: But you know, there's something there in this in this man that makes me hesitate to just

00:43:45.720 --> 00:43:48.160
[Amit Varma]: dismiss the possibility of the former.

00:43:48.160 --> 00:43:54.640
[Amit Varma]: All I can say is his core beliefs seem to me to be much more to do with Hindutva rather

00:43:54.640 --> 00:43:55.960
[Amit Varma]: than with the plus part.

00:43:55.960 --> 00:44:00.400
[Amit Varma]: And I've talked about Modi-twa as Hindutva plus.

00:44:00.400 --> 00:44:07.920
[Amit Varma]: But the plus part includes the Vikas Purush message somehow seem to be more tactical than

00:44:07.920 --> 00:44:08.920
[Amit Varma]: core beliefs.

00:44:08.920 --> 00:44:14.240
[Guest]: Another of your paradoxes actually feeds on from this and it's probably, you know, a natural

00:44:14.240 --> 00:44:18.640
[Guest]: consequence of this, which is that he makes these pluralist statements once in a while

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:21.800
[Guest]: and you think, I mean, that's a fairly liberal thing to say.

00:44:21.800 --> 00:44:26.480
[Guest]: But that is counterbalanced by his very polarizing campaign rhetoric, you know, which can be

00:44:26.480 --> 00:44:28.480
[Guest]: very communal and ugly.

00:44:28.480 --> 00:44:31.880
[Guest]: And at the same time, when he is in power as a prime minister and all of these things

00:44:31.880 --> 00:44:36.940
[Guest]: happen, lynchings happen and so on, there is a silence that almost seems tacit.

00:44:36.940 --> 00:44:38.840
[Guest]: And all of these kind of contradict each other.

00:44:38.840 --> 00:44:42.420
[Guest]: But you know, as you said, this the pulls and pressures you just described explain this

00:44:42.420 --> 00:44:43.420
[Guest]: as well.

00:44:43.420 --> 00:44:46.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, the pulls and pressures do explain this.

00:44:46.440 --> 00:44:47.760
[Guest]: You're quite right.

00:44:47.760 --> 00:44:52.520
[Guest]: And yeah, and they also explain another paradox where he talks of the Constitution as a holy

00:44:52.520 --> 00:44:57.080
[Guest]: book, but the RSS is, you know, holds a Manusmriti as a holy book.

00:44:57.080 --> 00:45:01.560
[Guest]: So again, it's that paradox is also kind of explained by this.

00:45:01.560 --> 00:45:05.640
[Amit Varma]: But it's not just that, you know, he actually says that Dindayal Upadhyay is his hero and

00:45:05.640 --> 00:45:11.240
[Amit Varma]: mentor when he came, became prime minister, he insisted that every single ministry hold

00:45:11.240 --> 00:45:16.040
[Amit Varma]: a seminar on the thoughts of Dindayal Upadhyay and he put Dindayal Upadhyay logos on all

00:45:16.040 --> 00:45:17.840
[Amit Varma]: the ministry letterheads and so on.

00:45:17.840 --> 00:45:22.440
[Amit Varma]: Now, the fact of the matter is Dindayal Upadhyay may have been a very interesting and inspiring

00:45:22.440 --> 00:45:23.440
[Amit Varma]: figure.

00:45:23.440 --> 00:45:27.160
[Amit Varma]: But one thing he was absolutely clear about was that he despised the Constitution and

00:45:27.160 --> 00:45:29.280
[Amit Varma]: wished to tear it up and discard it.

00:45:29.280 --> 00:45:35.200
[Amit Varma]: So you cannot on hand say that the Constitution is a holy book and on the other hand say that

00:45:35.200 --> 00:45:36.880
[Amit Varma]: you worship Dindayal Upadhyay.

00:45:36.880 --> 00:45:39.280
[Amit Varma]: The two thoughts are fundamentally incompatible.

00:45:39.280 --> 00:45:43.520
[Amit Varma]: Now one of these is insincere, and I believe it was the reference to the Constitution that

00:45:43.520 --> 00:45:44.720
[Amit Varma]: was insincere.

00:45:44.720 --> 00:45:50.560
[Amit Varma]: I think that Modi is indeed schooled in the Dindayal Upadhyay kind of approach.

00:45:50.560 --> 00:45:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And ideally, he and his acolytes in the BJP do want to change the Constitution.

00:45:56.000 --> 00:46:00.760
[Amit Varma]: But until they have the numbers in both houses, as well as in the state assemblies to amend

00:46:00.760 --> 00:46:03.040
[Amit Varma]: the Constitution, they can't do it.

00:46:03.040 --> 00:46:07.280
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, for the moment, tactically, it's useful to swear by the very Constitution

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:10.080
[Amit Varma]: that they're busy destroying the spirit of.

00:46:10.080 --> 00:46:14.400
[Guest]: But when he speaks of the Constitution as a holy book, who is he really speaking to?

00:46:14.400 --> 00:46:19.320
[Guest]: I mean, is it the case that he is secretly, he really wants the affection of the Lutyens

00:46:19.320 --> 00:46:21.080
[Guest]: elite who he disparages so much?

00:46:21.080 --> 00:46:26.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I think he wants the affection of the establishment, the media, the thinking classes

00:46:26.120 --> 00:46:27.800
[Amit Varma]: and so on in this country.

00:46:27.800 --> 00:46:29.200
[Amit Varma]: Or he wanted it at some point.

00:46:29.200 --> 00:46:33.240
[Amit Varma]: I think he, my own view is that the gloves are going to come off in April of 2019.

00:46:33.240 --> 00:46:35.960
[Amit Varma]: And we no longer see that kind of talk.

00:46:35.960 --> 00:46:39.880
[Amit Varma]: But certainly I think he did want the affection of everybody.

00:46:39.880 --> 00:46:42.520
[Amit Varma]: But more important, he wanted to disarm them.

00:46:42.520 --> 00:46:47.640
[Amit Varma]: You know, he couldn't necessarily win over a lot of these people in terms of affection.

00:46:47.640 --> 00:46:52.800
[Amit Varma]: But he had to at least convey the impression that he was no threat to the fundamental consensus

00:46:52.800 --> 00:46:54.760
[Amit Varma]: that had built this country.

00:46:54.760 --> 00:47:00.240
[Amit Varma]: And that's the only way, with the Vikas message and so on, that he could build up the support

00:47:00.240 --> 00:47:04.560
[Amit Varma]: base around the country that would enable him then to amend the Constitution.

00:47:04.560 --> 00:47:07.640
[Amit Varma]: Don't forget that he succeeded to the tune of 20 state governments.

00:47:07.640 --> 00:47:09.140
[Amit Varma]: He's now lost three.

00:47:09.140 --> 00:47:16.640
[Amit Varma]: But he had 20 state governments in the BJP kitty as recently as the last month of 2018.

00:47:16.640 --> 00:47:19.520
[Amit Varma]: And that means that he was well on his way to fulfilling his dream.

00:47:19.520 --> 00:47:23.880
[Amit Varma]: He had, with the NDA, 333 seats in the Lok Sabha.

00:47:23.880 --> 00:47:28.220
[Amit Varma]: And thanks to the state assemblies he now controlled, he was gradually creeping up to

00:47:28.220 --> 00:47:30.920
[Amit Varma]: a convincing majority in the Rajya Sabha.

00:47:30.920 --> 00:47:36.960
[Amit Varma]: With all of this, in say, three, four, five years' time, he would have been in a position

00:47:36.960 --> 00:47:40.560
[Amit Varma]: to write the Hindutva constitution of his dreams.

00:47:40.560 --> 00:47:45.520
[Amit Varma]: Now the fact is that it looks like the nation is going to stop him before he gets there.

00:47:45.520 --> 00:47:50.080
[Amit Varma]: Or that even if he inevitably becomes the dominant party in the Rajya Sabha, that he's

00:47:50.080 --> 00:47:54.160
[Amit Varma]: going to be stopped in the Lok Sabha in the 2019 general election.

00:47:54.160 --> 00:47:57.640
[Amit Varma]: So then my fears will again be dialed down.

00:47:57.640 --> 00:48:03.000
[Amit Varma]: But certainly I have no doubt, having looked at the convictions of the BJP and the Hindutva

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:08.840
[Amit Varma]: Brigade and the followers of Mr. Modi, that had he been able to retain this majority in

00:48:08.840 --> 00:48:14.080
[Amit Varma]: the Lok Sabha and add to it in a few years a majority in the Rajya Sabha, that we would

00:48:14.080 --> 00:48:19.480
[Amit Varma]: have seen him openly and nakedly saying, we need to strike certain words in the constitution,

00:48:19.480 --> 00:48:25.440
[Amit Varma]: we need to make India Hindu Rashtra with the Hindu faith as the official faith of the country,

00:48:25.440 --> 00:48:26.440
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth.

00:48:26.440 --> 00:48:30.400
[Amit Varma]: All of these are things that he and his followers have long believed, and they would finally

00:48:30.400 --> 00:48:32.280
[Amit Varma]: have been in a position to do it.

00:48:32.280 --> 00:48:37.440
[Amit Varma]: But the other talk was a means, it seems to me, to put themselves in a position to do

00:48:37.440 --> 00:48:38.440
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:48:38.440 --> 00:48:42.720
[Guest]: And you know, another paradox that is a big paradox, and I imagine both you and I would

00:48:42.720 --> 00:48:47.200
[Guest]: be upset that it's a paradox at all, is that he said all these beautiful things before

00:48:47.200 --> 00:48:50.360
[Guest]: the elections about minimum government, maximum governance.

00:48:50.360 --> 00:48:52.360
[Guest]: And as you point out, it's just the opposite.

00:48:52.360 --> 00:48:56.880
[Guest]: We've had maximum government and minimum governance where, you know, you talk about the ideal

00:48:56.880 --> 00:49:01.480
[Guest]: size of the cabinet and you say that, you know, one sort of rule of thumb was that it

00:49:01.480 --> 00:49:04.560
[Guest]: should be around 10% of the Lok Sabha or about 55 or whatever.

00:49:04.560 --> 00:49:09.280
[Guest]: And you even outline in great detail what you think the ideal number should be and why,

00:49:09.280 --> 00:49:14.760
[Guest]: which is about 40-45, which, you know, the argument seemed very convincing to me.

00:49:14.760 --> 00:49:20.000
[Guest]: And you have a telling anecdote about his early days about why he was drawn to the RSS

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:24.320
[Guest]: because, you know, it seemed to him that here was a group where everybody listened to one

00:49:24.320 --> 00:49:30.320
[Guest]: leader, which shows how his thinking from a very early stage is sort of a top down thinking.

00:49:30.320 --> 00:49:36.040
[Guest]: Now, you know, your expression of disappointment at him not living up to the slogan of minimum

00:49:36.040 --> 00:49:40.960
[Guest]: government, maximum governance also leads me to another larger paradox, which is that

00:49:40.960 --> 00:49:44.840
[Guest]: we have always been a nation of top down thinkers and large governments.

00:49:44.840 --> 00:49:49.360
[Guest]: I mean, Modi might have around 80 ministers right now, as you pointed out, but Manmohan

00:49:49.360 --> 00:49:53.800
[Guest]: Singh at 78 before this, as you mentioned in your book yourself.

00:49:53.800 --> 00:49:58.160
[Amit Varma]: And it's also true that we're the only country which has actually had to create a guideline

00:49:58.160 --> 00:50:02.240
[Amit Varma]: saying no more than 15% of the strength of the two houses, because otherwise governments

00:50:02.240 --> 00:50:07.040
[Amit Varma]: would have gone on and on appointing ministers and deputy ministers and parliamentary secretaries,

00:50:07.040 --> 00:50:12.680
[Amit Varma]: because ultimately the big flaw in the parliamentary system, one which I've decried in a different

00:50:12.680 --> 00:50:17.600
[Amit Varma]: book, India Shastra, is the fact that you are electing a legislator in order to form

00:50:17.600 --> 00:50:24.440
[Amit Varma]: the executive, which is a fundamental, to my mind, a flaw in the entire British system,

00:50:24.440 --> 00:50:26.400
[Amit Varma]: which we have taken on to ourselves.

00:50:26.400 --> 00:50:31.160
[Amit Varma]: And so what's happening is that once you get elected as part of the ruling party, what

00:50:31.160 --> 00:50:35.920
[Amit Varma]: you want to do is become a monthly or at least hold some other position the government can

00:50:35.920 --> 00:50:36.920
[Amit Varma]: give you.

00:50:36.920 --> 00:50:42.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, the fact is that thanks to the official guideline of 15%, they can't do that.

00:50:42.040 --> 00:50:49.360
[Amit Varma]: But even then, it's very striking that we have this incredibly centralized situation

00:50:49.360 --> 00:50:55.680
[Amit Varma]: where what Mr. Modi has realized is you hand out these various portfolios or SOPs to people,

00:50:55.680 --> 00:50:57.880
[Amit Varma]: but you keep all real power to yourself.

00:50:57.880 --> 00:51:02.560
[Amit Varma]: So you have your 18 ministers in the Modi government, but of that only one, and that's

00:51:02.560 --> 00:51:06.640
[Amit Varma]: Mr. Modi himself, actually has any power to decide anything.

00:51:06.640 --> 00:51:11.800
[Amit Varma]: Every other minister, first of all, has a secretary or a senior civil service that bypasses

00:51:11.800 --> 00:51:15.840
[Amit Varma]: him and goes and reports to the prime minister's office under Mr. Modi.

00:51:15.840 --> 00:51:20.760
[Amit Varma]: And second, the decisions are made with Mr. Modi's stamp and not that of the minister

00:51:20.760 --> 00:51:26.360
[Amit Varma]: himself or herself, with the result that ultimately it almost doesn't matter when you speak of

00:51:26.360 --> 00:51:32.800
[Amit Varma]: minimum government and maximum governance, what you're seeing is maximum centralized

00:51:32.800 --> 00:51:38.600
[Amit Varma]: government in the shape of the PMO, which is certainly the most top-down, most centralized

00:51:38.600 --> 00:51:42.360
[Amit Varma]: PMO we've seen since Indira Gandhi's emergency.

00:51:42.360 --> 00:51:46.320
[Amit Varma]: And you have at the same time inefficient governance, which is actually not maximum

00:51:46.320 --> 00:51:51.600
[Amit Varma]: governance or minimum governance, because a lot of decisions keep pending since the

00:51:51.600 --> 00:51:56.360
[Amit Varma]: people in the PMO are human beings and there's a limit to how many files they can process.

00:51:56.360 --> 00:52:00.640
[Amit Varma]: And so this government has the worst record in the filling of vacancies in the history

00:52:00.640 --> 00:52:04.960
[Amit Varma]: of democratic India, because every blessed vacancy has to be filled with the approval

00:52:04.960 --> 00:52:06.120
[Amit Varma]: of the PMO.

00:52:06.120 --> 00:52:10.800
[Amit Varma]: And lots and lots and lots of vacancies, everything from administrative tribunals to the Information

00:52:10.800 --> 00:52:16.640
[Amit Varma]: Commission to various other governmental bodies, pend and pend for weeks and months on end,

00:52:16.640 --> 00:52:21.560
[Amit Varma]: because there just isn't time for the staff of the PMO who are making 2,000 other decisions

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:23.920
[Amit Varma]: at the same time to also deal with this.

00:52:23.920 --> 00:52:29.320
[Guest]: Now, when it came to your opposition to 377 or your equally principled opposition to the

00:52:29.320 --> 00:52:33.400
[Guest]: death penalty, you were sort of like a lone voice in the political landscape.

00:52:33.400 --> 00:52:36.000
[Guest]: Is that also the case on the issue of minimum government?

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:40.680
[Guest]: Or, you know, is there a chance that we'll actually see a much smaller ministry if the

00:52:40.680 --> 00:52:42.080
[Guest]: Congress does come to power?

00:52:42.080 --> 00:52:48.720
[Amit Varma]: No, sir, I'm afraid you won't, because I think the logic of the Congress party would be that,

00:52:48.720 --> 00:52:53.000
[Amit Varma]: especially since it's going to be almost certainly a coalition government, and especially if

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:58.920
[Amit Varma]: it is a coalition government, that portfolios have to be sufficiently numerous in order

00:52:58.920 --> 00:53:01.680
[Amit Varma]: to keep various constituent elements happy.

00:53:01.680 --> 00:53:06.280
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, I don't think my ideas will go very far with a coalition government.

00:53:06.280 --> 00:53:10.720
[Amit Varma]: My most radical idea, which I am truly alone, but which I'm convinced would be beneficial

00:53:10.720 --> 00:53:16.320
[Amit Varma]: for this country, is to scrap the parliamentary system altogether and go for clear separation

00:53:16.320 --> 00:53:20.760
[Amit Varma]: of powers between the legislature and the executive, elect an executive president in

00:53:20.760 --> 00:53:25.520
[Amit Varma]: the center and an executive chief minister or governor in the states, and an elected,

00:53:25.520 --> 00:53:30.880
[Amit Varma]: by the way, mayor in the towns as well, who would actually be invulnerable to the whims

00:53:30.880 --> 00:53:36.400
[Amit Varma]: of a legislative majority, but would be able to have a free hand, plus the free budgetary

00:53:36.400 --> 00:53:41.920
[Amit Varma]: authority, to actually do whatever they promised in their campaigns to do and be held accountable

00:53:41.920 --> 00:53:44.160
[Amit Varma]: four or five years later.

00:53:44.160 --> 00:53:47.600
[Amit Varma]: Well they would be challenged by a legislature.

00:53:47.600 --> 00:53:51.760
[Amit Varma]: The legislature would reflect all the diverse interests in India today.

00:53:51.760 --> 00:53:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And so you'd have more or less the same kind of parliament you have, except that parliament

00:53:55.000 --> 00:53:57.080
[Amit Varma]: would not be constituting the executive.

00:53:57.080 --> 00:54:01.280
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it would be completely separate from the executive, would be questioning the executive

00:54:01.280 --> 00:54:03.960
[Amit Varma]: and holding it accountable on a day-to-day basis.

00:54:03.960 --> 00:54:09.600
[Amit Varma]: And it would actually be a far, far better system for the diversity of our country, and

00:54:09.600 --> 00:54:12.960
[Amit Varma]: at the same time a more efficient system, because the president could get on and get

00:54:12.960 --> 00:54:17.960
[Amit Varma]: work done instead of spending all his or her time in staying in power, which is what Mr.

00:54:17.960 --> 00:54:21.280
[Amit Varma]: Modi has been doing with his five years in office.

00:54:21.280 --> 00:54:24.520
[Guest]: And do you think something like that will ever be possible?

00:54:24.520 --> 00:54:29.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, I'm afraid, you know, major constitutional change of that nature requires a world-class

00:54:29.480 --> 00:54:30.800
[Amit Varma]: crisis to come about.

00:54:30.800 --> 00:54:34.760
[Amit Varma]: I don't see it happening quite so easily.

00:54:34.760 --> 00:54:39.080
[Amit Varma]: But you know, if there ever were a national cataclysm, a nuclear war or something, God

00:54:39.080 --> 00:54:43.440
[Amit Varma]: forbid, I don't want to want to ever happen, but if it did, and we literally had to build

00:54:43.440 --> 00:54:49.440
[Amit Varma]: up the pieces from rubble, this option should present itself to any sensible rethink at

00:54:49.440 --> 00:54:50.440
[Amit Varma]: that point.

00:54:50.440 --> 00:54:52.480
[Amit Varma]: And so I'm happy to lay it out there for posterity.

00:54:52.480 --> 00:54:55.560
[Guest]: I know we're running short of time and you have to get somewhere.

00:54:55.560 --> 00:55:00.720
[Guest]: So we'll quickly run through the rest of the paradoxes of Mr. Modi that you point out.

00:55:00.720 --> 00:55:04.880
[Guest]: Paradox to federalism, that there was a time where he claimed to be a believer in federalism,

00:55:04.880 --> 00:55:07.720
[Guest]: especially when he was the chief minister of Gujarat, of course.

00:55:07.720 --> 00:55:12.000
[Guest]: But he's acted in quite contrary ways once he's actually come to power at the center.

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Precisely.

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:17.240
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, as chief minister of Gujarat, he opposed anything that he could see as an

00:55:17.240 --> 00:55:22.080
[Amit Varma]: encroachment on state's rights, whether it was the counterterrorism center, whether it

00:55:22.080 --> 00:55:26.480
[Amit Varma]: was the Aadhaar implementation, whether it was GST, which he said took away the state's

00:55:26.480 --> 00:55:31.080
[Amit Varma]: rights to tax on the punish producer states, as he called them and so on.

00:55:31.080 --> 00:55:34.880
[Amit Varma]: The moment he becomes prime minister, somehow everything changes.

00:55:34.880 --> 00:55:39.240
[Amit Varma]: And as I joked, where you stand depends on where you sit.

00:55:39.240 --> 00:55:43.800
[Amit Varma]: He's sitting in Delhi in the prime minister's office and his stand is completely changed.

00:55:43.800 --> 00:55:45.560
[Guest]: That's really well said.

00:55:45.560 --> 00:55:51.160
[Guest]: Another Modi paradox is his desire to portray himself as a modern, tech friendly prime minister,

00:55:51.160 --> 00:55:55.840
[Guest]: but at the same time, this constant harking back to a glorious past, which is, of course,

00:55:55.840 --> 00:55:57.040
[Guest]: kind of mythical.

00:55:57.040 --> 00:56:00.960
[Guest]: And these two sort of collide in very awkward, uncomfortable ways, like his mention of how

00:56:00.960 --> 00:56:04.840
[Guest]: we did the first plastic surgery, which was Ganesha and so on.

00:56:04.840 --> 00:56:10.720
[Guest]: My broader question really here is beyond this obvious contradiction is that why is

00:56:10.720 --> 00:56:16.640
[Guest]: it that glorious past is such a key part of these kind of populist narratives, not just

00:56:16.640 --> 00:56:18.320
[Guest]: in India, but elsewhere as well?

00:56:18.320 --> 00:56:23.980
[Amit Varma]: Well, in India, there is a complete worldview which Modi has internalized and which is fundamental

00:56:23.980 --> 00:56:28.640
[Amit Varma]: to his thinking about the nature of the country, which is that India was this glorious, you

00:56:28.640 --> 00:56:35.280
[Amit Varma]: know, golden bird that got despoiled when the evil Muslims and then the evil Christians

00:56:35.280 --> 00:56:39.280
[Amit Varma]: came in and blocked its wings and despoiled it.

00:56:39.280 --> 00:56:45.200
[Amit Varma]: And that now a Hindu Hriday Samaraj has come back to restore this forgotten glory.

00:56:45.200 --> 00:56:49.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, if that is your narrative and that's your basic view of the history of India, which

00:56:49.920 --> 00:56:53.440
[Amit Varma]: I'm afraid it is, because when I wrote my book An Era of Darkness Attacking British

00:56:53.440 --> 00:56:58.320
[Amit Varma]: Colonialism, Modi, while hailing it, was making speeches about 1,200 years of foreign rule,

00:56:58.320 --> 00:57:03.480
[Amit Varma]: which I don't agree with, because to my mind, the Mughals and the other Muslim rulers before

00:57:03.480 --> 00:57:08.760
[Amit Varma]: them came to this country, settled here, and even if they did exploit or loot, they spent

00:57:08.760 --> 00:57:11.720
[Amit Varma]: the products of their exploitation and loot in India.

00:57:11.720 --> 00:57:15.480
[Amit Varma]: And they created some of the most beautiful buildings, architecture, monuments and cultural

00:57:15.480 --> 00:57:18.280
[Amit Varma]: legacies of which we are all the inheritors today.

00:57:18.280 --> 00:57:20.400
[Amit Varma]: So to my mind, they're not foreigners.

00:57:20.400 --> 00:57:25.680
[Amit Varma]: Whereas the British as imperialists did drain our resources to build their country, and

00:57:25.680 --> 00:57:28.720
[Amit Varma]: they didn't work in the interests of this country, but rather of their own.

00:57:28.720 --> 00:57:29.720
[Amit Varma]: So there is a difference.

00:57:29.720 --> 00:57:34.360
[Amit Varma]: Now, having said all of that, if Mr. Modi's view of Indian history is what it is that

00:57:34.360 --> 00:57:39.880
[Amit Varma]: I've summarized to you, then a whole set of corollaries follow from it.

00:57:39.880 --> 00:57:44.980
[Amit Varma]: Number one, that you've got to glorify that past, because it was so great.

00:57:44.980 --> 00:57:49.680
[Amit Varma]: So everything about it is made to look fantastic in order to diminish what followed.

00:57:49.680 --> 00:57:55.720
[Amit Varma]: Second, you have to demonize the successors of those whom you despise for having done

00:57:55.720 --> 00:58:00.720
[Amit Varma]: terrible things to your country, and therefore you demonize Muslims and Christians.

00:58:00.720 --> 00:58:07.680
[Amit Varma]: And third, you present yourself as the one who is restoring a gloried, fabled past.

00:58:07.680 --> 00:58:11.520
[Amit Varma]: So you are not merely sort of advocating something new.

00:58:11.520 --> 00:58:13.720
[Amit Varma]: You are coming back to ancient glories.

00:58:13.720 --> 00:58:19.760
[Amit Varma]: But you are doing so using all the technologies available to you in the 21st century, because

00:58:19.760 --> 00:58:23.800
[Amit Varma]: India is not going to be second to anybody when it comes to technology.

00:58:23.800 --> 00:58:30.920
[Amit Varma]: So as I joked in the book, the image you sought to portray is of a leader who is comfortable

00:58:30.920 --> 00:58:35.360
[Amit Varma]: clicking a mouse with one hand while brandishing a threshold with the other.

00:58:35.360 --> 00:58:36.640
[Guest]: That's a brilliant image.

00:58:36.640 --> 00:58:40.900
[Guest]: I'll quickly run through three of the other paradoxes I noted, and then I can get to some

00:58:40.900 --> 00:58:42.840
[Guest]: more questions to end the show with.

00:58:42.840 --> 00:58:47.560
[Guest]: The seventh paradox I found was where you, you know, you've quoted Modi saying to you,

00:58:47.560 --> 00:58:51.600
[Guest]: in fact, that how much he likes criticism, and he wants people to criticize and that

00:58:51.600 --> 00:58:53.560
[Guest]: makes the government stronger and all that.

00:58:53.560 --> 00:58:58.520
[Guest]: But at the same time, in practice, what we found is that he foments in-house trolls,

00:58:58.520 --> 00:59:04.280
[Guest]: he can be very petty and vindictive when it comes to, you know, people who criticize him

00:59:04.280 --> 00:59:06.320
[Guest]: and completely in the other direction.

00:59:06.320 --> 00:59:11.560
[Guest]: And a similar hypocrisy is when he speaks about how parliamentary debate is good, and

00:59:11.560 --> 00:59:13.880
[Guest]: it strengthens the nation and so on.

00:59:13.880 --> 00:59:19.620
[Guest]: But at the same time, the BJP has been second to none in disrupting parliament over time.

00:59:19.620 --> 00:59:24.040
[Guest]: And you also point out that it's not entirely their fault that you know, the anti-defection

00:59:24.040 --> 00:59:29.280
[Guest]: law of 1985 sort of made and I've had an episode on just that law in the past, and sort of

00:59:29.280 --> 00:59:33.880
[Guest]: made it compulsory for parliamentarians to vote with the party whip.

00:59:33.880 --> 00:59:38.560
[Guest]: And the natural consequence of that would be that parliamentary debate would necessarily

00:59:38.560 --> 00:59:40.660
[Guest]: go down because it became inconsequential.

00:59:40.660 --> 00:59:44.840
[Guest]: You could actually taut up the votes according to an Excel sheet.

00:59:44.840 --> 00:59:45.840
[Amit Varma]: Correct.

00:59:45.840 --> 00:59:50.040
[Amit Varma]: So my many objections to the parliamentary system include that precise detail of the

00:59:50.040 --> 00:59:54.920
[Amit Varma]: way it works in our country, where thanks to the anti-defection law, because that was

00:59:54.920 --> 00:59:59.400
[Amit Varma]: of course passed with very good intentions to prevent unprincipled defections, we've

00:59:59.400 --> 01:00:03.340
[Amit Varma]: now created a situation where the individual legislator is no longer allowed to speak his

01:00:03.340 --> 01:00:08.640
[Amit Varma]: mind or vote his conscience, but is obliged to adhere to the whip of his party, failing

01:00:08.640 --> 01:00:13.360
[Amit Varma]: which he could actually lose a seat in parliament that he's worked so hard to win.

01:00:13.360 --> 01:00:17.800
[Amit Varma]: And therefore he swallows his words and bites his tongue in order to prevent that kind of

01:00:17.800 --> 01:00:18.800
[Amit Varma]: consequence for him.

01:00:18.800 --> 01:00:22.920
[Amit Varma]: I do believe it's damaged the principle of representation very greatly.

01:00:22.920 --> 01:00:27.760
[Amit Varma]: But that's gotten you away from the paradoxes of Mr. Moody, which you're quite right to

01:00:27.760 --> 01:00:30.320
[Amit Varma]: point to that he does have these various paradoxes.

01:00:30.320 --> 01:00:36.540
[Amit Varma]: You also should take the paradox of his great talent for publicity and self-promotion using

01:00:36.540 --> 01:00:41.200
[Amit Varma]: the world media and his refusal to be accountable to the media in the form of a press conference.

01:00:41.200 --> 01:00:45.160
[Amit Varma]: He's the only prime minister in his entire five years who has never held a press conference.

01:00:45.160 --> 01:00:47.960
[Amit Varma]: He only wants scripted questions.

01:00:47.960 --> 01:00:52.040
[Amit Varma]: And when even in interaction with his own party workers, he was asked an uncomfortable

01:00:52.040 --> 01:00:56.780
[Amit Varma]: question, his discomfort and his refusal to answer was an embarrassment.

01:00:56.780 --> 01:01:03.560
[Amit Varma]: This is very much at odds with somebody who claims to be an easygoing, frank, accessible,

01:01:03.560 --> 01:01:05.680
[Guest]: dissent-tolerating individual.

01:01:05.680 --> 01:01:10.520
[Guest]: And sort of moving on from the paradoxes, you also talk about how the Hindutva vision

01:01:10.520 --> 01:01:15.400
[Guest]: of the world, which, you know, Moditwa also plays into is a very masculine vision where

01:01:15.400 --> 01:01:21.480
[Guest]: he boasts about his 56 inch ki chhati and you know, for all the noises they make about

01:01:21.480 --> 01:01:27.840
[Guest]: making India safer for women, their attitude seems very misogynistic in the sense that,

01:01:27.840 --> 01:01:32.360
[Guest]: like you said in your book, they view women as goddesses or mothers, both to be worshipped

01:01:32.360 --> 01:01:36.800
[Guest]: and protected, but they have no concept of how to deal with women who are neither.

01:01:36.800 --> 01:01:37.800
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:01:37.800 --> 01:01:38.800
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:01:38.800 --> 01:01:45.080
[Amit Varma]: And this whole business of women's equality, and that's linked to women's safety as well,

01:01:45.080 --> 01:01:51.560
[Amit Varma]: is exacerbated by the galloping onset of modernity because people are suddenly finding women,

01:01:51.560 --> 01:01:56.680
[Amit Varma]: especially, you know, people moving from rural India, from relatively traditional lives to

01:01:56.680 --> 01:02:02.520
[Amit Varma]: cities are seeing women dressed in ways that they've never seen, behaving in ways with

01:02:02.520 --> 01:02:06.960
[Amit Varma]: a degree of freedom and autonomy that they've never seen or got used to, leading independent

01:02:06.960 --> 01:02:09.480
[Amit Varma]: lives, walking alone and all of that.

01:02:09.480 --> 01:02:12.800
[Amit Varma]: And because they're unable to adjust to and cope with this, because they've never been

01:02:12.800 --> 01:02:17.880
[Amit Varma]: trained to respect women as anything other than as mothers or goddesses, they've ended

01:02:17.880 --> 01:02:20.680
[Amit Varma]: up, I'm afraid, assaulting many of these women.

01:02:20.680 --> 01:02:26.560
[Amit Varma]: So even women's safety is linked to this inability to recognize the equality of women.

01:02:26.560 --> 01:02:31.160
[Amit Varma]: And all of this is part of a social paradox that goes beyond Modi.

01:02:31.160 --> 01:02:34.800
[Amit Varma]: Modi's masculinity is actually partly affectation.

01:02:34.800 --> 01:02:39.880
[Amit Varma]: As I pointed out in the book, the 56 inch chest where an Atchikan needed to be stitched

01:02:39.880 --> 01:02:41.960
[Amit Varma]: turned out to actually be 50.

01:02:41.960 --> 01:02:45.160
[Amit Varma]: So there's a lot of exaggeration there in that masculinity.

01:02:45.160 --> 01:02:49.400
[Amit Varma]: And certainly, you know, yoga rather than bodybuilding is his thing.

01:02:49.400 --> 01:02:54.640
[Amit Varma]: So I don't think we need to detain ourselves too long on those tropes.

01:02:54.640 --> 01:03:00.440
[Amit Varma]: But part of this, called the muscularity that the Hindutva movement needs to advertise to

01:03:00.440 --> 01:03:03.660
[Amit Varma]: show its inherent superiority to others.

01:03:03.660 --> 01:03:11.600
[Amit Varma]: So the masculinity is caught up in the muscularity, in the militaristic language and jingoism,

01:03:11.600 --> 01:03:16.940
[Amit Varma]: in the praise for the army, often not matched by actual concrete support for the armed forces.

01:03:16.940 --> 01:03:24.040
[Amit Varma]: But all of these things are part of this Hindutva assertiveness, which is what passes for right-wing

01:03:24.040 --> 01:03:26.280
[Amit Varma]: ideology in our country today.

01:03:26.280 --> 01:03:29.600
[Guest]: And you know, there's a quote from you in your book, which really struck me when you

01:03:29.600 --> 01:03:34.640
[Guest]: were talking about the difference between Hinduism as it is and Hinduism as, Hinduism

01:03:34.640 --> 01:03:39.000
[Guest]: as a different political parties kind of view it, where you talk about how the view of it

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:44.160
[Guest]: evolved, quote, from the soft Brahmanism of the Congress Party to the tough Kshatriya

01:03:44.160 --> 01:03:46.240
[Guest]: warrior tradition, stop quote.

01:03:46.240 --> 01:03:50.360
[Guest]: And we've already discussed and agreed on why there is a problem with that tough Kshatriya

01:03:50.360 --> 01:03:52.220
[Guest]: warrior tradition, so to say.

01:03:52.220 --> 01:03:57.640
[Guest]: But I also found the phrase soft Brahmanism of the Congress Party, you know, mildly disturbing,

01:03:57.640 --> 01:03:59.080
[Guest]: which leads me to my next question.

01:03:59.080 --> 01:04:02.760
[Guest]: And I don't want to, you know, sort of put you in a sort of spot.

01:04:02.760 --> 01:04:03.760
[Amit Varma]: But when we talk about

01:04:03.760 --> 01:04:08.720
[Amit Varma]: That wasn't my characterization, but the RSS's and Golwalkar say things like, you know, look

01:04:08.720 --> 01:04:12.240
[Amit Varma]: at how all our Hindu gods are shown with weapons.

01:04:12.240 --> 01:04:14.320
[Amit Varma]: What is all this Gandhi and Ahimsa talk?

01:04:14.320 --> 01:04:16.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, we are a militaristic people.

01:04:16.880 --> 01:04:18.680
[Amit Varma]: So they saw this as soft Brahmanism.

01:04:18.680 --> 01:04:22.800
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, the principal Congress leaders were not only Brahmins.

01:04:22.800 --> 01:04:28.960
[Amit Varma]: Of course, Nehruji was, Panditji was a Brahmin, but Gandhiji and Sardar Patel were not.

01:04:28.960 --> 01:04:33.360
[Amit Varma]: So you know, I think one shouldn't generalize on the caste front of the Congress Party.

01:04:33.360 --> 01:04:34.360
[Guest]: That's my bad.

01:04:34.360 --> 01:04:35.360
[Guest]: I shouldn't have attributed that to you.

01:04:35.360 --> 01:04:36.360
[Guest]: Apologies for that.

01:04:36.360 --> 01:04:38.040
[Guest]: It was my paraphrase of what they felt.

01:04:38.040 --> 01:04:39.040
[Guest]: Fair enough.

01:04:39.040 --> 01:04:40.040
[Guest]: Fair enough.

01:04:40.040 --> 01:04:41.040
[Guest]: I buy that.

01:04:41.040 --> 01:04:46.800
[Guest]: And, you know, my sort of larger question to you is that, aren't there paradoxes that

01:04:46.800 --> 01:04:49.200
[Guest]: go beyond Mr. Modi to your own party?

01:04:49.200 --> 01:04:54.080
[Guest]: For example, Rahul Gandhi talks of inner party democracy, but he's himself an unelected leader.

01:04:54.080 --> 01:04:59.040
[Guest]: They talk against the communalism of the BJP, but they are also pursuing that Hindu vote

01:04:59.040 --> 01:05:03.240
[Amit Varma]: bank as you know, through the trips to Kedarnath.

01:05:03.240 --> 01:05:04.240
[Amit Varma]: There are differences there.

01:05:04.240 --> 01:05:10.920
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I'll be brief because I am now well past the hour mark that we discussed.

01:05:10.920 --> 01:05:15.320
[Amit Varma]: But just to say that, number one, as far as the inner party democracy argument is concerned,

01:05:15.320 --> 01:05:19.120
[Amit Varma]: you're right, absolutely, there is no widespread electoral process.

01:05:19.120 --> 01:05:23.240
[Amit Varma]: But you're wrong in the sense that anyone in the Congress will tell you that if you

01:05:23.240 --> 01:05:28.760
[Amit Varma]: had a free and fair election tomorrow amongst Congress workers and put any Congress leader

01:05:28.760 --> 01:05:32.720
[Amit Varma]: you can name against Rahul Gandhi, that person would lose to Rahul Gandhi.

01:05:32.720 --> 01:05:39.400
[Amit Varma]: The party, the party workers, the party organization wants a son of the Gandhi Nehru family to

01:05:39.400 --> 01:05:40.480
[Amit Varma]: lead it.

01:05:40.480 --> 01:05:43.200
[Amit Varma]: And that is definitely the case.

01:05:43.200 --> 01:05:48.240
[Amit Varma]: And if there was a perception at one point that Rahul Gandhi was a reluctant leader,

01:05:48.240 --> 01:05:53.520
[Amit Varma]: it's partially because he had been press ganged into this to a great extent by the demands

01:05:53.520 --> 01:05:55.260
[Amit Varma]: of party workers.

01:05:55.260 --> 01:05:56.820
[Amit Varma]: So that's on the first point.

01:05:56.820 --> 01:06:00.760
[Amit Varma]: On the second point, I would disagree respectfully because I don't think what the Congress is

01:06:00.760 --> 01:06:04.000
[Amit Varma]: doing is soft Hindutva, as has been alleged.

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:11.880
[Amit Varma]: It is very much the advocacy of an inclusive Hinduism as opposed to the kind of exclusionary

01:06:11.880 --> 01:06:16.920
[Amit Varma]: and bigoted Hindutva that the BJP practices and propagates.

01:06:16.920 --> 01:06:22.040
[Amit Varma]: So when the communal polarization is thought to be attempted by the BJP, though when they

01:06:22.040 --> 01:06:24.880
[Amit Varma]: speak of Hindutva, we don't want to share that space with them.

01:06:24.880 --> 01:06:28.800
[Amit Varma]: But when they say we're the only party that respects Hinduism, Hindu culture and speaks

01:06:28.800 --> 01:06:31.600
[Amit Varma]: up for Hindu interests, we turn around and say, what are you talking about?

01:06:31.600 --> 01:06:33.560
[Amit Varma]: They go to temples, we go to temples too.

01:06:33.560 --> 01:06:35.600
[Amit Varma]: We worship and respect the same things you do.

01:06:35.600 --> 01:06:39.520
[Amit Varma]: So now that we've neutralized that argument, can we set that aside and talk about vikas?

01:06:39.520 --> 01:06:41.960
[Amit Varma]: Can we talk about whether you're a chidinavakam?

01:06:41.960 --> 01:06:46.360
[Amit Varma]: Can we talk about the kind of conditions that you've been reduced to by this government?

01:06:46.360 --> 01:06:50.320
[Amit Varma]: So it's not Hinduism in the sense of Hindutva.

01:06:50.320 --> 01:06:56.760
[Amit Varma]: It is Hinduism as a tactic to neutralize a particularly potent part of the BJP's appeal

01:06:56.760 --> 01:07:01.400
[Amit Varma]: in order to focus on the issues that we believe really matter to the Indian voter.

01:07:01.400 --> 01:07:02.400
[Guest]: Fair enough.

01:07:02.400 --> 01:07:05.280
[Guest]: I won't ask any more follow up questions on this particular subject because I know we're

01:07:05.280 --> 01:07:06.280
[Guest]: running out of time.

01:07:06.280 --> 01:07:10.440
[Guest]: One final question before I end, which is really a two part question.

01:07:10.440 --> 01:07:14.120
[Guest]: Given both the politics of this country and given the social scenario where we have a

01:07:14.120 --> 01:07:18.520
[Guest]: jobs crisis, we have an agricultural crisis and, you know, the demographic dividend, so

01:07:18.520 --> 01:07:20.780
[Guest]: to say, is turning out to be a demographic disaster.

01:07:20.780 --> 01:07:26.200
[Guest]: Given all of this, what makes you hope and what makes you despair about India in the

01:07:26.200 --> 01:07:27.200
[Guest]: next 10 years?

01:07:27.200 --> 01:07:32.640
[Amit Varma]: What makes me hope is the extraordinary capacity of the Indian people, you know, and I've lived

01:07:32.640 --> 01:07:36.840
[Amit Varma]: around the world and I've seen Indians thrive and succeed everywhere, and there's something

01:07:36.840 --> 01:07:38.440
[Amit Varma]: about us as a people.

01:07:38.440 --> 01:07:43.840
[Amit Varma]: We are by and large quick learners, hard workers, effective result producers, except it seems

01:07:43.840 --> 01:07:44.840
[Amit Varma]: in India.

01:07:44.840 --> 01:07:48.400
[Amit Varma]: And we need to get our act together here better, partly because the systems have held us down.

01:07:48.400 --> 01:07:50.280
[Amit Varma]: We need to improve those.

01:07:50.280 --> 01:07:53.200
[Amit Varma]: But the second reason I'm hopeful is because I do see change.

01:07:53.200 --> 01:07:54.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, change has occurred.

01:07:54.960 --> 01:07:58.560
[Amit Varma]: As I said earlier, in a different context, the India I grew up in is not the India I

01:07:58.560 --> 01:08:03.840
[Amit Varma]: return to, and it cuts right across the board in politics and economics and social and cultural

01:08:03.840 --> 01:08:07.000
[Amit Varma]: relations, in caste equations, you name it.

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:08.520
[Amit Varma]: There have been some real changes.

01:08:08.520 --> 01:08:10.240
[Amit Varma]: Some changes have been for the worse.

01:08:10.240 --> 01:08:14.440
[Amit Varma]: The growing communalization has shocked me because I hear things being said from public

01:08:14.440 --> 01:08:19.120
[Amit Varma]: platforms that when I was young would have been impolite to express even behind closed

01:08:19.120 --> 01:08:20.920
[Amit Varma]: doors in private living rooms.

01:08:20.920 --> 01:08:24.920
[Amit Varma]: So there is now a change in that communal discourse that I think is deplorable.

01:08:24.920 --> 01:08:27.520
[Amit Varma]: But for the most part, the changes that have occurred have been positive.

01:08:27.520 --> 01:08:32.160
[Amit Varma]: I find a very self-confident India that genuinely believes it can hold its own with the rest

01:08:32.160 --> 01:08:33.360
[Amit Varma]: of the world.

01:08:33.360 --> 01:08:34.360
[Amit Varma]: So I'm not too worried.

01:08:34.360 --> 01:08:39.880
[Amit Varma]: And I think that the capacity for self-correction that our democracy gives us means that where

01:08:39.880 --> 01:08:44.720
[Amit Varma]: we've gone wrong in the last five years, or if you want to say it, in the last 10 years,

01:08:44.720 --> 01:08:47.280
[Amit Varma]: can be corrected in the next five or the next 10.

01:08:47.280 --> 01:08:51.800
[Amit Varma]: And I think that the elections offer the Indian public a chance to correct that.

01:08:51.800 --> 01:08:56.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, striking one of the paradoxes you and I never discussed was the paradox that

01:08:56.440 --> 01:09:01.880
[Amit Varma]: we have at the helm of the nation somebody who is perhaps the most eloquent rhetorician

01:09:01.880 --> 01:09:06.840
[Amit Varma]: who has featured on the Indian political stage since independence, at least in Hindi, the

01:09:06.840 --> 01:09:09.920
[Amit Varma]: most eloquent and compelling orator.

01:09:09.920 --> 01:09:15.600
[Amit Varma]: And yet, when some of the defining moments in the insecurity of our fellow Indians has

01:09:15.600 --> 01:09:20.200
[Amit Varma]: occurred, the suicide of Rohit Memla, the flogging of those Dalits in Jaipur, the murder

01:09:20.200 --> 01:09:24.440
[Amit Varma]: of Pahelwa Khan on YouTube, the murder of an Indian Air Force, Haridwar's father, Mohammed

01:09:24.440 --> 01:09:29.560
[Amit Varma]: Lakhlaq on the suspicion of carrying beef, etc., etc., the horrendous number of cow vigilante

01:09:29.560 --> 01:09:32.680
[Amit Varma]: Bob lynchings, all of these things have happened.

01:09:32.680 --> 01:09:36.500
[Amit Varma]: This eloquent rhetorician has gone mysteriously silent.

01:09:36.500 --> 01:09:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And I think that paradox points to one of the biggest defects of the Modi approach.

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:47.180
[Amit Varma]: Modi is diagnosing the problems of India very effectively in his speeches, blaming them

01:09:47.180 --> 01:09:49.900
[Amit Varma]: all on the past, of course, rather than on himself.

01:09:49.900 --> 01:09:54.700
[Amit Varma]: But then, when it comes to providing moral leadership through his words, he has gone

01:09:54.700 --> 01:09:55.960
[Amit Varma]: silent on us.

01:09:55.960 --> 01:10:00.940
[Amit Varma]: I think what we need in this country is a leadership that is both inclusive and cooperative,

01:10:00.940 --> 01:10:06.060
[Amit Varma]: that actually provides a certain moral direction, but that derives its strength from the Indian

01:10:06.060 --> 01:10:07.320
[Amit Varma]: people.

01:10:07.320 --> 01:10:12.540
